{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Andria", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction     = Diocese \n|name             = Andria\n|latin            = Dioecesis Andriensis \n|image            = Cattedrale0558 1 copia.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px \n|caption          = [[Andria Cathedral]]\n|country          = Italy\n|metropolitan     = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto|Bari-Bitonto]] \n|rite             = [[Latin Rite]]\n|established      = 11th Century\n|cathedral        = Cattedrale di S. Maria Assunta\n|cocathedral      = \n|area_km2         = 799  \n|population       = 141,229 \n|population_as_of = 2015\n|catholics        = 140,000 (est.)  \n|catholics_percent= 99.1 \n|priests          = 69 (diocesan)<br>20 (religious Orders)\n|pope             = {{Incumbent pope}}\n|bishop           = [[Luigi Mansi]] \n|coadjutor        = \n|auxiliary_bishops= \n|map              = Roman Catholic Diocese of Andria in Italy.jpg\n|map_alt          = locator map for diocese of Andria\n|patron           = Richard of Andria  <ref>[http://saints.sqpn.com/patrons-of-the-diocese-of-andria-italy/ Saints.SQPN.com]</ref> \n}}\n\nThe Italian Catholic '''diocese of Andria''' is in [[Apulia]], seated at [[Andria Cathedral]] which is built over a church dedicated to [[St. Peter]], about ten miles southwest of Trani. It is a [[suffragan]] of the [[archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto]]. The diocese has 39 parishes, with one priest for every 1,573 Catholics.<ref name=CathHierAndria>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dandr.html \"Diocese of Andria\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016.{{Self-published source|date=April 2019}}</ref><ref name=GCathAndria>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/andr0.htm \"Diocese of Andria\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016.{{Self-published source|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nTradition assigns the Christian origin of [[Andria]] to an Englishman, St. Richard, chosen as bishop by [[Pope Gelasius I]], about 492 [[AD]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Giuseppe Lanave |author2=Antonio Marrazzo |author3=Vincenzo Schiavone |title=San Riccardo protettore di Andria: riscoperto come vescovo del vangelo e della carit\u00e0 nei bassorilievi della cattedrale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwNrHQAACAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Grafiche Guglielmi|location=Andria|language=Italian}}</ref> The story has been dismissed as fable by some scholars.<ref>Lanzoni, pp. 302-303: ''Le prove addotte dall'Ughelli e da altri scrittori per mostrare che le diocesi di Andria, Bisceglie (Vigiliae), Canne, Conversano (Cupersanum) e Ruvo (Rubum) sono anteriori al 604, non hanno alcun valore.'' ''...Riccardus ... porvienne dale leggende graganiche....''  Kehr, p. 307: ''Quo autem tempore episcopatus institutus sit, penitus ignoratur neque admitti potest pia Andrensium traditio, quae s. Riccardum Anglicum saec. V primum Andren. ep. fuisse voluit....'' ('...the pious tradition of Andria that the Englishman Richard was the first bishop of Andria in the fifth century cannot be admitted....').</ref> A Bishop Christopher of Andria is reported at the II Council of Nicaea in 787, but inspection shows that he was Christopher Bishop of Saint Cyriacus (Gerace).<ref>J.D. Mansi (ed.), Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio, editio novissima, Tomus XIII (Florence: A. Zatta 1767), p. 383. Ughelli, p. 925. Gams, p. 848. See Louis Duchesne, (1902), \"Les \u00e9v\u00e8ch\u00e9s de Calabre,\" {{cite book|title=M\u00e9langes Paul Fabre: \u00e9tudes d'histoire du moyen \u00e2ge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z76FAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA292|year=1902|publisher=A. Picard et fils|location=Paris|language=French|page=15}}</ref>\n\nThe diocese dates probably back to the time of [[Gelasius II]], elected Pope in 1118. The earliest known bishop of Andria, whose name is not preserved, took part in the translation of the body of S. Nicolas Peregrinus in Trani in 1143.<ref>Ughelli, VII, pp. 903, 925. Gams, p. 848.</ref> Bishop [[Richard of Andria]] was present at the [[Eleventh Ecumenical Council]] (Third Lateran, 1179) held under [[Pope Alexander III]].<ref>John Joseph A'Becket (1907). [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/01475b.htm \"Diocese of Andria.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia''. Vol. 1. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1907; retrieved: 28 April 2019.</ref>\n\nIt was united with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Montepeloso|diocese of Montepeloso]], from 1452 to 1479.\n\n==Bishops==\n===Diocese of Andria===\n''Erected: 11th Century''<br>\n''Latin Name: Andriensis''<br>\n''Metropolitan: [[Archdiocese of Trani]]''\n:'''...'''\n*Richard (attested 1158\u20131196)<ref>Bishop Richardus was present at the Lateran Council of 1179. J. D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XXII (Venice: A. Zatta 1778), p. 461. Ughelli, VII, pp. 925-926. Kamp, p. 563.</ref>\n*Mathaeus (attested 1243)<ref>Kamp, p. 564.</ref>\n*frater Joannes (attested 1269\u20131274)<ref>Kamp, p. 564.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Placidus (attested 1290, 1304)<ref>Placidus: Eubel, I, p. 89.</ref>\n*Joannes (attested 1318)\n*Dominicus (attested 1319)\n*Joannes de Alexandria, O.E.S.A. (10 November 1348 \u2013 1349)<ref>Eubel, I, pp. 89-90.</ref>\n*Andreas, O.E.S.A. (14 March 1349 \u2013 ? )\n*Joannes (attested 1356)\n*Marcus\n*Lucidus de Nursia, O.E.S.A. (20 December 1374 \u2013 1379/1380)<ref>Lucidus was removed by Urban VI, probably because he supported Clement VII in the Great Western Schism.</ref>\n*Franciscus (c. 1380 \u2013 ? )<ref>Franciscus was provided by Urban VI in the wake of the beginning of the Great Western Schism. Eubel, I, p. 90</ref>\n*Milillus Sabanicae, O.E.S.A. (16 January 1392 \u2013 1418)<ref>Milillus was a native of Andria, and had previously been Bishop of Salpe (1400\u20131413). He served as Bishop of Andria for eighteen years. Ughelli, pp. 926-927. Eubel, I, p. 90, 431.</ref>\n*Franciscus de Nigris (12 August 1418 \u2013 1435?)<ref>Franciscus had previously been Bishop of Salpe (1413\u20131418). Ughelli, p. 927. Eubel, I, p. 90, 431. Gams intrudes an Andrea Doria, O.S.B., who was actually Bishop of Andros (1427\u20131436). Eubel, I, p. 89.</ref>\n*Joannes Donadei (14 November 1435 \u2013 1451)<ref>Donadei:  Eubel, II, p. 88.</ref>\n\n===Diocese of Andria-Montepeloso===\n''United: 1452 with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Montepeloso|Diocese of Montepeloso]]''<br>\n''Latin Name: Andriensis-Montis Pelusii''\n*Antonellus, O.Min. (20 September 1452 \u2013 1463?)<ref>Antonellus had previously been Bishop of Callipolis (Thrace) (1451\u20131452). Eubel, II, pp. 88, 115.</ref>\n*Matthaeus Antonius (3 April 1463 \u2013 1465?)\n*Franciscus de Bertinis (20 October 1465 \u2013 18 September 1471)<ref>Bishop Francesco de Bertini was transferred to the diocese of Capaccio on 18 September 1471. Eubel, II, pp. 88, 118.</ref>\n*Martin Sotomayor, O.Carm. (18 September 1471 \u2013 March 1477)<ref>Sotomayor had previously been Bishop of Chrysopolis (Arabia) (1440\u20131450). Eubel, II, pp. 88, 128.</ref>\n*Angelus Florus (1477 \u2013 1495)<ref>Gams, p. 849.</ref>\n\n===Diocese of Andria===\n====1479 to 1800====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n''Split: 1479 into the Diocese of Andria and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Montepeloso|Diocese of Montepeloso]]''<br>\n''Latin Name: Andriensis''\n*Angelus Florus (1477 \u2013 1495)<ref>Florus was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). He renovated the choir stalls in the cathedral, and reroofed the episcopal residence. Ughelli, p. 931. Gams, p. 849.</ref>\n*[[Geronimo Porcari]] (26 April 1495 \u2013 1503 Died)\n*[[Antonio de Roccamoro]], [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (1503 \u20131515 Resigned)<ref>Fra Antonio needed a dispensation for illegitimacy. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'', III, p. 109 with note 3.</ref> \n*[[Andrea Pastore (bishop)|Andrea Pastore]] (26 March 1515 \u2013 1516 Died)<ref>Pastor was only in his 27th year when appointed.  He required a dispensation. Eubel III, p. 109, with n. 4.</ref>\n*[[Simone de Nor]] (12 December 1516 \u2013 1517 Died) \n*[[Niccol\u00f2 Fieschi]] (1517\u20131517 Resigned)\n*[[Giovanni Francesco Fieschi]] (1517\u20131565 Resigned)\n*[[Luca Fieschi]] (1566\u20131582 Appointed, [[Bishop of Albenga]])\n*[[Luca Antonio Resta]] (1582\u20131597 Died)<ref>Resta held the degree ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). He had previously been Bishop of Castro (1565\u20131578), and Bishop of Nicotera (1578\u20131582). Eubel, III, pp. 109, 158, 258.</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Bassi]] (1598\u20131603 Died)<ref>Vincenzo Basso was a priest of the diocese of Cremona, who held the degree of Doctor of Canon Law. He had previously been Bishop of Sebenico in Dalmatia (1589\u20131598). Eubel, III, pp. 109, 299. Gauchat, ''Hierarchia catholica'' IV, p. 83 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Antonio de Franchis]], [[Congregation of Clerics Regular of the Divine Providence|C.R.]] (1604\u20131625 Died)<ref>De Franchis had previously been Bishop of Ravello (1600\u20131603), but he resigned before 30 July 1603. He was not appointed to Andria until 23 January 1604. Gauchat, IV, pp. 83 with note 3; 292 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Caputo]] (1625\u20131626 Died)<ref>Caputo: Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Alessandro Strozzi (bishop of San Miniato)|Alessandro Strozzi]] (1626\u20131632)<ref>Strozzi was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of San Miniato|San Miniato]]) : Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Felice Franceschini]], [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (26 April 1632 \u2013 8 October 1641 Died)<ref>Franceschini: Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 6.</ref>\n*[[Ascanio Cassiani]] (16 December 1641 \u2013 1657 Died)<ref>Cassiani was born at Monteregali (diocese of Reate) in 1606. He was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 7.</ref>\n*[[Alessandro Egizio]] (17 December 1657 \u2013 April 1689 Died)<ref>Egizio was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 8.</ref>\n*[[Pietro Vecchia (bishop)]], [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (1690 \u2013 19 December 1691)<ref>Vecchia was born in Venice in 1628. He was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Molfetta|Molfetta]] on 19 December 1691. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 3; 265 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Francesco Antonio Triveri]], [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (21 January 1692 \u2013 24 September 1696)<ref>Triveri was born in Biella (diocese of Vercelli). He was a Master of theology, and became Inquisitor of Padua in 1672; in August 1674 he moved to the same post in Florence. In 1692 he became general secretary of the Inquisition. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome by Cardinal Marcantonio Barbarigo on 27 January 1692.  He was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Melfi e Rapolla|Melfi]] on 24 September 1696. He died in May 1697. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 4; p. 265 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Andrea Ariani]] (14 January 1697 \u2013 1706 Died)<ref>Ariani: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 85 with note 5.</ref>\n*Nicola Adinolfi (6 December 1706 \u2013 1715 Died)<ref>Adinolfi: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 85 with note 6.</ref> \n*Giovanni Paolo Torti Rogadei, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (1718\u20131726)<ref>Torti was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Avellino e Frigento|Avellino]] on 9 December 1726. He died on 19 August 1742. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 7; 109 with note 9.</ref>\n*Cherubino Tommaso Nobilione, [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (1726\u20131743 Resigned)<ref>Nobilione: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 8.</ref> \n*Domenico Anelli (20 May 1743\u2013 14 July 1756 Died)<ref>Anelli  was born in Andria in 1698. He was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law) (Rome, Sapienza 1739). He was Vicar-General of Andria and co-visitor of the diocese. He was Bishop of Acerno (1739\u20131743), consecrated in Rome on 1 February 1739 by the titular Archbishop of Tyre, Giovanni di Lerma. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, pp. 63, 83 with note 2.</ref>\n*Francesco Ferrante (1757\u20131772 Died)<ref>Ferrante: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 83 with note 3.</ref>\n*Saverio Palica, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (1773\u20131791 Died)<ref>Born in 1714, Palica was a native of Barletta (diocese of Trani). A member of the Celestine Congregation of the Benedictine Order, he served as master of novices, Dean of the royal monastery of Sulmona, abbot of the monastery of Barletta, Monte S. Aagelo Luceriae, and abbot of the monastery of the Holy Trinity in Santa Severa. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome on 14 March 1773 by Cardinal Lazzaro Pallavicino. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 83 with note 4.</ref>\n*Salvatore Maria Lombardi (27 February 1792 \u2013 1821 Died)<ref>Lombardi was born at Maddaloni (diocese of Caserta) in 1739. He was  ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law) (Naples 1761). He was a vicar general of the dioceses of Boiano, Caiazzo, Taranto, and Materano. He was nominated bishop of Andria by the King of Naples on 16 December 1791, and approved by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 27 February 1792. He was consecrated in Rome on 4 March 1792 by Cardinal Francesco Zelada. Cappelletti, XXI, p. 82. Gams, p. 849. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 83 with note 5.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====since 1818====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n:''1818: Territory Added from the suppressed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Minervino Murge|Diocese of Minervino Murge]]''\n\n*Giovanni Battista Bolognese (1822 \u2013 1830 Died)<ref>Bolognese had previously been Bishop of Termoli (1818\u20131822). Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 74, 366.</ref>\n*Giuseppe Cosenza (1832\u20131850)<ref>Born in 1788, Cosenza was a native of Naples, held a doctorate in theology, and was Canon Theologian of the Cathedral Chapter of Naples. Cosenza was transferred to the diocese of [[Archbishop of Capua|Capua]] on 10 September 1850. He was named a Cardinal by [[Pope Pius IX]] on 30 September 1850. He died on 30 March 1863. Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 74; VIII, p. 51, 180. {{cite book|author=Martin Br\u00e4uer|title=Handbuch der Kardin\u00e4le: 1846-2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=363pBQAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=De Gruyter|location=Berlin|language=German|isbn=978-3-11-026947-5|page=1862}}</ref>\n*Giovanni Giuseppe Longobardi (1852\u20131870 Died)\n*Federico Maria Galdi (1872\u20131899 Died)\n*Giuseppe Staiti di Brancaleone (1899\u20131916 Died)\n*[[Eugenio Tosi]], [[O.Ss.C.A.]] (1917\u20131922 Appointed, [[Archbishop of Milan]])\n*Alessandro Macchi (1922\u20131930 Appointed, [[Bishop of Como]])\n*Ferdinando Bernardi (1931\u20131935 Appointed, [[Archbishop of Taranto]])\n*Paolo Rostagno (1935\u20131939 Appointed, [[Bishop of Ivrea]])\n*[[Giuseppe Di Donna]], [[O.SS.T.]] (1940\u20131952 Died)\n*Luigi Pirelli (1952\u20131957 Resigned)\n*Francesco Brustia (1957\u20131969 Resigned)\n*Giuseppe Lanave (1969\u20131988 Retired)\n*[[Raffaele Calabro]] (1988\u20132016 Retired)\n*Luigi Mansi (2016\u2013)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n\n===Reference works===\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 2|date=1914|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 3|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon}} pp.&nbsp;898\u2013899. (Use with caution; obsolete)\n*{{cite book|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=Hierarchia catholica  IV (1592-1667)|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol04eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi  V (1667-1730)|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi  VI (1730-1799)|date=1958|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol06eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia Catholica medii et recentioris aevi sive summorum pontificum, S. R. E. cardinalium, ecclesiarum antistitum series... A pontificatu Pii PP. VII (1800) usque ad pontificatum Gregorii PP. XVI (1846)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgyItwAACAAJ|volume=Volume VII|year=1968|publisher=Libr. Regensburgiana|location=Monasterii|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ritzler, Remigius|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi... A Pontificatu PII PP. IX (1846) usque ad Pontificatum Leonis PP. XIII (1903)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi...  A pontificatu Pii PP. X (1903) usque ad pontificatum Benedictii PP. XV (1922)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Cappelletti|first=Giuseppe|title=Le chiese d'Italia dalla loro origine sino ai nostri giorni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aXFTAAAAcAAJ|volume=Volume vigesimoprimo (21)|year=1870|publisher=Antonelli|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=394\u2013399}}\n*{{cite book|last=D'Avino|first=Vincenzio|title=Cenni storici sulle chiese arcivescovili, vescovili, e prelatizie (nullius) del regno delle due Sicilie |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fUIsAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA168|year=1848|publisher=dalle stampe di Ranucci|location=Naples|language=Italian|pages=18\u201320}}\n*Kamp, Norbert (1975). ''Kirche und Monarchie im staufischen K\u00f6nigreich Sizilien: [http://digi20.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb00042154_00001.html?prox=true&phone=true&ngram=true&seriesTitle_str=%7BKirche+und+Monarchie+im+staufischen+K%C3%B6nigreich+Sizilien%7D&hl=scan&fulltext=Kamp+Kirche+und+Monarchie&mode=simple&context=Kamp%20Kirche%20und%20Monarchie I. Prosopographische Grundlegung, Bistumer und  Bist\u00fcmer und Bisch\u00f6fe des Konigreichs 1194\u20131266: 2. Apulien und Calabrien]'' M\u00fcnchen: Wilhelm Fink 1975.\n*Kehr, Paulus Fridolin (1962). ''Italia pontificia. Regesta pontificum Romanorum.'' [http://sul-derivatives.stanford.edu/derivative?CSNID=00002440&mediaType=application/pdf Vol. IX: Samnia \u2013 Apulia \u2013 Lucania].  Berlin: Weidmann. (in Latin), pp.&nbsp;307\u2013308.\n*{{cite book|author=Lanzoni, Francesco|title=Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fzlSAQAAMAAJ|year=1927|publisher=Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana|location=Rome|language=Italian|pages=312\u2013317}}\n*Loconte, R. (1962). ''I vescovi di Andria'' (Andria 1962). (in Italian)\n*{{cite book|last=Romano|first=Michele|title=Saggio sulla storia di Molfetta dall'epoca dell'antica Respa sino al 1840 del dottor fisico Michele Romano: 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n9gs3oyJbikC&pg=PA123|volume=Parte seconda|year=1842b|publisher=De Bonis|location=Napoli|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Niccol\u00f2|title=Italia sacra,  sive De Episcopis Italiae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfyRMcKY2qgC|volume=Tomus septimus (VII)|year=1721|publisher=apud Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=920\u2013935}}\n\n==Acknowledgment==\n{{Catholic|wstitle=Diocese of Andria|first=John Joseph|last=a'Becket}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Bari-Bitonto}}\n\n{{coord|41|13|54|N|16|18|30|E|type:city_source:kolossus-plwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Apulia|Andria]]\n[[Category:Andria]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 11th century|Andria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction     = Diocese \n|name             = Andria\n|latin            = Dioecesis Andriensis \n|image            = Cattedrale0558 1 copia.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px \n|caption          = [[Andria Cathedral]]\n|country          = Italy\n|metropolitan     = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto|Bari-Bitonto]] \n|rite             = [[Latin Rite]]\n|established      = 11th Century\n|cathedral        = Cattedrale di S. Maria Assunta\n|cocathedral      = \n|area_km2         = 799  \n|population       = 141,229 \n|population_as_of = 2015\n|catholics        = 140,000 (est.)  \n|catholics_percent= 99.1 \n|priests          = 69 (diocesan)<br>20 (religious Orders)\n|pope             = {{Incumbent pope}}\n|bishop           = [[Luigi Mansi]] \n|coadjutor        = \n|auxiliary_bishops= \n|map              = Roman Catholic Diocese of Andria in Italy.jpg\n|map_alt          = locator map for diocese of Andria\n|patron           = Richard of Andria  <ref> [http://saints.sqpn.com/patrons-of-the-diocese-of-andria-italy/ Saints.SQPN.com] </ref> \n}}\n\nThe Italian Catholic '''diocese of Andria''' is in [[Apulia]], seated at [[Andria Cathedral]] which is built over a church dedicated to [[St. Peter]], about ten miles southwest of Trani. It is a [[suffragan]] of the [[archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto]]. The diocese has 39 parishes, with one priest for every 1,573 Catholics.<ref name=CathHierAndria>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dandr.html \"Diocese of Andria\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016.{{Self-published source|date=April 2019}}</ref><ref name=GCathAndria>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/andr0.htm \"Diocese of Andria\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016.{{Self-published source|date=April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nTradition assigns the Christian origin of [[Andria]] to an Englishman, St. Richard, chosen as bishop by [[Pope Gelasius I]], about 492 [[AD]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Giuseppe Lanave |author2=Antonio Marrazzo |author3=Vincenzo Schiavone |title=San Riccardo protettore di Andria: riscoperto come vescovo del vangelo e della carit\u00e0 nei bassorilievi della cattedrale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TwNrHQAACAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Grafiche Guglielmi|location=Andria|language=Italian}}</ref> The story has been dismissed as fable by some scholars.<ref>Lanzoni, pp. 302-303: ''Le prove addotte dall'Ughelli e da altri scrittori per mostrare che le diocesi di Andria, Bisceglie (Vigiliae), Canne, Conversano (Cupersanum) e Ruvo (Rubum) sono anteriori al 604, non hanno alcun valore.'' ''...Riccardus ... porvienne dale leggende graganiche....''  Kehr, p. 307: ''Quo autem tempore episcopatus institutus sit, penitus ignoratur neque admitti potest pia Andrensium traditio, quae s. Riccardum Anglicum saec. V primum Andren. ep. fuisse voluit....'' ('...the pious tradition of Andria that the Englishman Richard was the first bishop of Andria in the fifth century cannot be admitted....').</ref> A Bishop Christopher of Andria is reported at the II Council of Nicaea in 787, but inspection shows that he was Christopher Bishop of Saint Cyriacus (Gerace).<ref> J.D. Mansi (ed.), Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio, editio novissima, Tomus XIII (Florence: A. Zatta 1767), p. 383. Ughelli, p. 925. Gams, p. 848. See Louis Duchesne, (1902), \"Les \u00e9v\u00e8ch\u00e9s de Calabre,\" {{cite book|title=M\u00e9langes Paul Fabre: \u00e9tudes d'histoire du moyen \u00e2ge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z76FAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA292|year=1902|publisher=A. Picard et fils|location=Paris|language=French|page=15}}</ref>\n\nThe diocese dates probably back to the time of [[Gelasius II]], elected Pope in 1118. The earliest known bishop of Andria, whose name is not preserved, took part in the translation of the body of S. Nicolas Peregrinus in Trani in 1143.<ref>Ughelli, VII, pp. 903, 925. Gams, p. 848.</ref> Bishop [[Richard of Andria]] was present at the [[Eleventh Ecumenical Council]] (Third Lateran, 1179) held under [[Pope Alexander III]].<ref> John Joseph A'Becket (1907). [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/01475b.htm \"Diocese of Andria.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia''. Vol. 1. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1907; retrieved: 28 April 2019.</ref>\n\nIt was united with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Montepeloso|diocese of Montepeloso]], from 1452 to 1479.\n\n==Bishops==\n===Diocese of Andria===\n''Erected: 11th Century''<br>\n''Latin Name: Andriensis''<br>\n''Metropolitan: [[Archdiocese of Trani]]''\n:'''...'''\n*Richard (attested 1158\u20131196)<ref>Bishop Richardus was present at the Lateran Council of 1179. J. D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, Tomus XXII (Venice: A. Zatta 1778), p. 461. Ughelli, VII, pp. 925-926. Kamp, p. 563.</ref>\n*Mathaeus (attested 1243)<ref>Kamp, p. 564.</ref>\n*frater Joannes (attested 1269\u20131274)<ref>Kamp, p. 564.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Placidus (attested 1290, 1304)<ref>Placidus: Eubel, I, p. 89.</ref>\n*Joannes (attested 1318)\n*Dominicus (attested 1319)\n*Joannes de Alexandria, O.E.S.A. (10 November 1348 \u2013 1349)<ref>Eubel, I, pp. 89-90.</ref>\n*Andreas, O.E.S.A. (14 March 1349 \u2013 ? )\n*Joannes (attested 1356)\n*Marcus\n*Lucidus de Nursia, O.E.S.A. (20 December 1374 \u2013 1379/1380)<ref>Lucidus was removed by Urban VI, probably because he supported Clement VII in the Great Western Schism.</ref>\n*Franciscus (c. 1380 \u2013 ? )<ref>Franciscus was provided by Urban VI in the wake of the beginning of the Great Western Schism. Eubel, I, p. 90</ref>\n*Milillus Sabanicae, O.E.S.A. (16 January 1392 \u2013 1418)<ref>Milillus was a native of Andria, and had previously been Bishop of Salpe (1400\u20131413). He served as Bishop of Andria for eighteen years. Ughelli, pp. 926-927. Eubel, I, p. 90, 431.</ref>\n*Franciscus de Nigris (12 August 1418 \u2013 1435?)<ref>Franciscus had previously been Bishop of Salpe (1413\u20131418). Ughelli, p. 927. Eubel, I, p. 90, 431. Gams intrudes an Andrea Doria, O.S.B., who was actually Bishop of Andros (1427\u20131436). Eubel, I, p. 89.</ref>\n*Joannes Donadei (14 November 1435 \u2013 1451)<ref>Donadei:  Eubel, II, p. 88.</ref>\n\n===Diocese of Andria-Montepeloso===\n''United: 1452 with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Montepeloso|Diocese of Montepeloso]]''<br>\n''Latin Name: Andriensis-Montis Pelusii''\n*Antonellus, O.Min. (20 September 1452 \u2013 1463?)<ref>Antonellus had previously been Bishop of Callipolis (Thrace) (1451\u20131452). Eubel, II, pp. 88, 115.</ref>\n*Matthaeus Antonius (3 April 1463 \u2013 1465?)\n*Franciscus de Bertinis (20 October 1465 \u2013 18 September 1471)<ref>Bishop Francesco de Bertini was transferred to the diocese of Capaccio on 18 September 1471. Eubel, II, pp. 88, 118.</ref>\n*Martin Sotomayor, O.Carm. (18 September 1471 \u2013 March 1477)<ref>Sotomayor had previously been Bishop of Chrysopolis (Arabia) (1440\u20131450). Eubel, II, pp. 88, 128.</ref>\n*Angelus Florus (1477 \u2013 1495)<ref>Gams, p. 849.</ref>\n\n===Diocese of Andria===\n====1479 to 1800====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n''Split: 1479 into the Diocese of Andria and the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Montepeloso|Diocese of Montepeloso]]''<br>\n''Latin Name: Andriensis''<br>\n*Angelus Florus (1477 \u2013 1495)<ref>Florus was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). He renovated the choir stalls in the cathedral, and reroofed the episcopal residence. Ughelli, p. 931. Gams, p. 849.</ref>\n*[[Geronimo Porcari]] (26 April 1495 \u2013 1503 Died)\n*[[Antonio de Roccamoro]], [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (1503 \u20131515 Resigned)<ref>Fra Antonio needed a dispensation for illegitimacy. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'', III, p. 109 with note 3.</ref> \n*[[Andrea Pastore (bishop)|Andrea Pastore]] (26 March 1515 \u2013 1516 Died)<ref>Pastor was only in his 27th year when appointed.  He required a dispensation. Eubel III, p. 109, with n. 4.</ref>\n*[[Simone de Nor]] (12 December 1516 \u2013 1517 Died) \n*[[Niccol\u00f2 Fieschi]] (1517\u20131517 Resigned)\n*[[Giovanni Francesco Fieschi]] (1517\u20131565 Resigned)\n*[[Luca Fieschi]] (1566\u20131582 Appointed, [[Bishop of Albenga]])\n*[[Luca Antonio Resta]] (1582\u20131597 Died)<ref>Resta held the degree ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). He had previously been Bishop of Castro (1565\u20131578), and Bishop of Nicotera (1578\u20131582). Eubel, III, pp. 109, 158, 258.</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Bassi]] (1598\u20131603 Died)<ref>Vincenzo Basso was a priest of the diocese of Cremona, who held the degree of Doctor of Canon Law. He had previously been Bishop of Sebenico in Dalmatia (1589\u20131598). Eubel, III, pp. 109, 299. Gauchat, ''Hierarchia catholica'' IV, p. 83 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Antonio de Franchis]], [[Congregation of Clerics Regular of the Divine Providence|C.R.]] (1604\u20131625 Died)<ref>De Franchis had previously been Bishop of Ravello (1600\u20131603), but he resigned before 30 July 1603. He was not appointed to Andria until 23 January 1604. Gauchat, IV, pp. 83 with note 3; 292 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Caputo]] (1625\u20131626 Died)<ref>Caputo: Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Alessandro Strozzi (bishop of San Miniato)|Alessandro Strozzi]] (1626\u20131632)<ref>Strozzi was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of San Miniato|San Miniato]]) : Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Felice Franceschini]], [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (26 April 1632 \u2013 8 October 1641 Died)<ref>Franceschini: Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 6.</ref>\n*[[Ascanio Cassiani]] (16 December 1641 \u2013 1657 Died)<ref>Cassiani was born at Monteregali (diocese of Reate) in 1606. He was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 7.</ref>\n*[[Alessandro Egizio]] (17 December 1657 \u2013 April 1689 Died)<ref>Egizio was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). Gauchat, IV, p. 83 with note 8.</ref>\n*[[Pietro Vecchia (bishop)]], [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (1690 \u2013 19 December 1691)<ref>Vecchia was born in Venice in 1628. He was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Molfetta|Molfetta]] on 19 December 1691. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 3; 265 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Francesco Antonio Triveri]], [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (21 January 1692 \u2013 24 September 1696)<ref>Triveri was born in Biella (diocese of Vercelli). He was a Master of theology, and became Inquisitor of Padua in 1672; in August 1674 he moved to the same post in Florence. In 1692 he became general secretary of the Inquisition. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome by Cardinal Marcantonio Barbarigo on 27 January 1692.  He was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Melfi e Rapolla|Melfi]] on 24 September 1696. He died in May 1697. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 4; p. 265 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Andrea Ariani]] (14 January 1697 \u2013 1706 Died)<ref>Ariani: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 85 with note 5.</ref>\n*Nicola Adinolfi (6 December 1706 \u2013 1715 Died)<ref>Adinolfi: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 85 with note 6.</ref> \n*Giovanni Paolo Torti Rogadei, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (1718\u20131726)<ref>Torti was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Avellino e Frigento|Avellino]] on 9 December 1726. He died on 19 August 1742. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 7; 109 with note 9.</ref>\n*Cherubino Tommaso Nobilione, [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (1726\u20131743 Resigned)<ref>Nobilione: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 85 with note 8.</ref> \n*Domenico Anelli (20 May 1743\u2013 14 July 1756 Died)<ref>Anelli  was born in Andria in 1698. He was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law) (Rome, Sapienza 1739). He was Vicar-General of Andria and co-visitor of the diocese. He was Bishop of Acerno (1739\u20131743), consecrated in Rome on 1 February 1739 by the titular Archbishop of Tyre, Giovanni di Lerma. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, pp. 63, 83 with note 2.</ref>\n*Francesco Ferrante (1757\u20131772 Died)<ref>Ferrante: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 83 with note 3.</ref>\n*Saverio Palica, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (1773\u20131791 Died)<ref>Born in 1714, Palica was a native of Barletta (diocese of Trani). A member of the Celestine Congregation of the Benedictine Order, he served as master of novices, Dean of the royal monastery of Sulmona, abbot of the monastery of Barletta, Monte S. Aagelo Luceriae, and abbot of the monastery of the Holy Trinity in Santa Severa. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome on 14 March 1773 by Cardinal Lazzaro Pallavicino. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 83 with note 4.</ref>\n*Salvatore Maria Lombardi (27 February 1792 \u2013 1821 Died)<ref>Lombardi was born at Maddaloni (diocese of Caserta) in 1739. He was  ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law) (Naples 1761). He was a vicar general of the dioceses of Boiano, Caiazzo, Taranto, and Materano. He was nominated bishop of Andria by the King of Naples on 16 December 1791, and approved by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 27 February 1792. He was consecrated in Rome on 4 March 1792 by Cardinal Francesco Zelada. Cappelletti, XXI, p. 82. Gams, p. 849. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 83 with note 5.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====since 1818====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n:''1818: Territory Added from the suppressed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Minervino Murge|Diocese of Minervino Murge]]'' \n\n*Giovanni Battista Bolognese (1822 \u2013 1830 Died)<ref>Bolognese had previously been Bishop of Termoli (1818\u20131822). Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 74, 366.</ref>\n*Giuseppe Cosenza (1832\u20131850)<ref>Born in 1788, Cosenza was a native of Naples, held a doctorate in theology, and was Canon Theologian of the Cathedral Chapter of Naples. Cosenza was transferred to the diocese of [[Archbishop of Capua|Capua]] on 10 September 1850. He was named a Cardinal by [[Pope Pius IX]] on 30 September 1850. He died on 30 March 1863. Ritzler-Sefrin, VII, pp. 74; VIII, p. 51, 180. {{cite book|author=Martin Br\u00e4uer|title=Handbuch der Kardin\u00e4le: 1846-2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=363pBQAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=De Gruyter|location=Berlin|language=German|isbn=978-3-11-026947-5|page=1862}}</ref>\n*Giovanni Giuseppe Longobardi (1852\u20131870 Died)\n*Federico Maria Galdi (1872\u20131899 Died)\n*Giuseppe Staiti di Brancaleone (1899\u20131916 Died)\n*[[Eugenio Tosi]], [[O.Ss.C.A.]] (1917\u20131922 Appointed, [[Archbishop of Milan]])\n*Alessandro Macchi (1922\u20131930 Appointed, [[Bishop of Como]])\n*Ferdinando Bernardi (1931\u20131935 Appointed, [[Archbishop of Taranto]])\n*Paolo Rostagno (1935\u20131939 Appointed, [[Bishop of Ivrea]])\n*[[Giuseppe Di Donna]], [[O.SS.T.]] (1940\u20131952 Died)\n*Luigi Pirelli (1952\u20131957 Resigned)\n*Francesco Brustia (1957\u20131969 Resigned)\n*Giuseppe Lanave (1969\u20131988 Retired)\n*[[Raffaele Calabro]] (1988\u20132016 Retired)\n*Luigi Mansi (2016\u2013)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n\n===Reference works===\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 2|date=1914|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 3|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon}} pp.&nbsp;898-899. (Use with caution; obsolete)\n*{{cite book|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=Hierarchia catholica  IV (1592-1667)|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol04eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi  V (1667-1730)|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi  VI (1730-1799)|date=1958|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol06eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia Catholica medii et recentioris aevi sive summorum pontificum, S. R. E. cardinalium, ecclesiarum antistitum series... A pontificatu Pii PP. VII (1800) usque ad pontificatum Gregorii PP. XVI (1846)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgyItwAACAAJ|volume=Volume VII|year=1968|publisher=Libr. Regensburgiana|location=Monasterii|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ritzler, Remigius|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi... A Pontificatu PII PP. IX (1846) usque ad Pontificatum Leonis PP. XIII (1903)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi...  A pontificatu Pii PP. X (1903) usque ad pontificatum Benedictii PP. XV (1922)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Cappelletti|first=Giuseppe|title=Le chiese d'Italia dalla loro origine sino ai nostri giorni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aXFTAAAAcAAJ|volume=Volume vigesimoprimo (21)|year=1870|publisher=Antonelli|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=394-399}}\n*{{cite book|last=D'Avino|first=Vincenzio|title=Cenni storici sulle chiese arcivescovili, vescovili, e prelatizie (nullius) del regno delle due Sicilie |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fUIsAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA168|year=1848|publisher=dalle stampe di Ranucci|location=Naples|language=Italian|pages=18-20}}\n*Kamp, Norbert (1975). ''Kirche und Monarchie im staufischen K\u00f6nigreich Sizilien: [http://digi20.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb00042154_00001.html?prox=true&phone=true&ngram=true&seriesTitle_str=%7BKirche+und+Monarchie+im+staufischen+K%C3%B6nigreich+Sizilien%7D&hl=scan&fulltext=Kamp+Kirche+und+Monarchie&mode=simple&context=Kamp%20Kirche%20und%20Monarchie I. Prosopographische Grundlegung, Bistumer und  Bist\u00fcmer und Bisch\u00f6fe des Konigreichs 1194\u20131266: 2. Apulien und Calabrien]'' M\u00fcnchen: Wilhelm Fink 1975.\n*Kehr, Paulus Fridolin (1962). ''Italia pontificia. Regesta pontificum Romanorum.'' [http://sul-derivatives.stanford.edu/derivative?CSNID=00002440&mediaType=application/pdf Vol. IX: Samnia \u2013 Apulia \u2013 Lucania].  Berlin: Weidmann. (in Latin), pp. 307-308.\n*{{cite book|author=Lanzoni, Francesco|title=Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fzlSAQAAMAAJ|year=1927|publisher=Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana|location=Rome|language=Italian|pages=312\u2013317}}\n*Loconte, R. (1962). ''I vescovi di Andria'' (Andria 1962). (in Italian)\n*{{cite book|last=Romano|first=Michele|title=Saggio sulla storia di Molfetta dall'epoca dell'antica Respa sino al 1840 del dottor fisico Michele Romano: 2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n9gs3oyJbikC&pg=PA123|volume=Parte seconda|year=1842b|publisher=De Bonis|location=Napoli|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Niccol\u00f2|title=Italia sacra,  sive De Episcopis Italiae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfyRMcKY2qgC|volume=Tomus septimus (VII)|year=1721|publisher=apud Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=920\u2013935}}\n\n==Acknowledgment==\n{{Catholic|wstitle=Diocese of Andria|first=John Joseph|last=a'Becket}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Bari-Bitonto}}\n\n{{coord|41|13|54|N|16|18|30|E|type:city_source:kolossus-plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Apulia|Andria]]\n[[Category:Andria]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 11th century|Andria]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Andria"}
{"title_page": "William H. Wood (American football)", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Bill Wood (American football)}}\n{{other uses|William H. Wood (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = William H. Wood\n| image = William H. Wood.png\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1900|9|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Waterbury, Connecticut]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1988|6|7|1900|9|6}}\n| death_place = [[Easton, Maryland]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1921\u20131924\n| player_team2 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n| player_sport3 = Basketball\n| player_years4 = 1921\u20131925\n| player_team4 = [[Army Black Knights men's basketball|Army]]\n| player_sport5 = Baseball\n| player_years6 = 1922\u20131925\n| player_team6 = [[Army Black Knights baseball|Army]]\n| player_positions = [[Fullback (gridiron football)|Fullback]] (football)\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1925\u20131928\n| coach_team2 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1932\u20131938\n| coach_team3 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1938\u20131940\n| coach_team4 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n| overall_record = 12\u201313\u20133\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''William Holmes Wood''' (September 6, 1900<ref>Military Times/Hall of Valor</ref> \u2013 June 7, 1988) was an [[American football]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]] player, coach of football, and [[United States Army]] officer.  He served as the head football coach at the [[United States Military Academy]] from 1938 to 1940, compiling a record of 12\u201313\u20133.  Wood was born in [[Waterbury, Connecticut]] and raised in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]].  He attended [[Johns Hopkins University]] before transferring to West Point, where he lettered in three sports and graduated in 1925.  Serving in China and Europe during [[World War II]], Wood was chief of staff of the [[13th Armored Division (United States)|13th Armored Division]]. His decorations included the [[Legion of Merit]].<ref>Military Times/Hall of Valor</ref> He retired from the Army in 1956 after rising to the rank of [[brigadier general]].  Wood died at the age of 87 on June 7, 1988 at the William Hill Health Care Center in [[Easton, Maryland]].  He had been stricken with [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Former Army football coach Wood dies |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NTpRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lzMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5016,917323 |newspaper=The Evening News |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=June 10, 1988 |accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Army Black Knights football|Army Cadets]]\n | conf      = NCAA independent\n | startyear = 1938\n | endyear   = 1940\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1938 college football season|1938]]\n | name         = [[1938 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 8\u20132\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1939 college football season|1939]]\n | name         = [[1939 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 3\u20134\u20132\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1940 college football season|1940]]\n | name         = [[1940 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 1\u20137\u20131\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Army\n | overall    = 12\u201313\u20133\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 12\u201313\u20133\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|49338222}}\n\n{{Army Black Knights football coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, William H.}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights baseball players]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football coaches]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Waterbury, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n\n{{1930s-collegefootball-coach-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Bill Wood (American football)}}\n:''For other uses, see [[William H. Wood (disambiguation)]]''\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = William H. Wood\n| image = William H. Wood.png\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1900|9|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Waterbury, Connecticut]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1988|6|7|1900|9|6}}\n| death_place = [[Easton, Maryland]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_sport1 = Football\n| player_years2 = 1921\u20131924\n| player_team2 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n| player_sport3 = Basketball\n| player_years4 = 1921\u20131925\n| player_team4 = [[Army Black Knights men's basketball|Army]]\n| player_sport5 = Baseball\n| player_years6 = 1922\u20131925\n| player_team6 = [[Army Black Knights baseball|Army]]\n| player_positions = [[Fullback (gridiron football)|Fullback]] (football)\n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1925\u20131928\n| coach_team2 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1932\u20131938\n| coach_team3 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1938\u20131940\n| coach_team4 = [[Army Black Knights football|Army]]\n| overall_record = 12\u201313\u20133\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''William Holmes Wood''' (September 6, 1900<ref>Military Times/Hall of Valor</ref> \u2013 June 7, 1988) was an [[American football]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]] player, coach of football, and [[United States Army]] officer.  He served as the head football coach at the [[United States Military Academy]] from 1938 to 1940, compiling a record of 12\u201313\u20133.  Wood was born in [[Waterbury, Connecticut]] and raised in [[Baltimore|Baltimore, Maryland]].  He attended [[Johns Hopkins University]] before transferring to West Point, where he lettered in three sports and graduated in 1925.  Serving in China and Europe during [[World War II]], Wood was chief of staff of the [[13th Armored Division (United States)|13th Armored Division]]. His decorations included the [[Legion of Merit]].<ref>Military Times/Hall of Valor</ref> He retired from the Army in 1956 after rising to the rank of [[brigadier general]].  Wood died at the age of 87 on June 7, 1988 at the William Hill Health Care Center in [[Easton, Maryland]].  He had been stricken with [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Former Army football coach Wood dies |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=NTpRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=lzMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5016,917323 |newspaper=The Evening News |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=June 10, 1988 |accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Army Black Knights football|Army Cadets]]\n | conf      = NCAA independent\n | startyear = 1938\n | endyear   = 1940\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1938 college football season|1938]]\n | name         = [[1938 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 8\u20132\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1939 college football season|1939]]\n | name         = [[1939 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 3\u20134\u20132\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1940 college football season|1940]]\n | name         = [[1940 Army Cadets football team|Army]]\n | overall      = 1\u20137\u20131\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Army\n | overall    = 12\u201313\u20133\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 12\u201313\u20133\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|49338222}}\n\n{{Army Black Knights football coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wood, William H.}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football fullbacks]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights baseball players]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football coaches]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights football players]]\n[[Category:Army Black Knights men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Waterbury, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n\n{{1930s-collegefootball-coach-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Standardized hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_H._Wood_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Anagni-Alatri", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Anagni-Alatri\n| latin             = Dioecesis Anagnina-Alatrina\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Vue d'ensemble cath\u00e9drale Santa-Maria d'Anagni.JPG\n| image_size        =  255px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = [[Anagni]] Cathedral\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = Italy\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = Immediately subject to the Holy See\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 787\n| population        = 90,908\n| population_as_of  = 2018\n| catholics         = 88,508<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 97.4\n| parishes          = 56<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 5th century\n| cathedral         = Basilica Cattedrale di Maria SS. Annunziata (Anagni)\n| cocathedral       = [[Alatri Cathedral|Basilica Concattedrale di S. Paolo Apostolo]] (Alatri)\n| patron            = \n| priests           = 35 (diocesan)<br />22 (Religious Orders)<br />3 Permanent Deacons<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = [[Lorenzo Loppa]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.diocesianagnialatri.it/ www.diocesianagnialatri.it]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n\nThe Italian Catholic '''Diocese of Anagni-Alatri''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Anagnina-Alatrina}}), in [[Lazio]], has existed since 1986. In that year the [[Diocese of Alatri]] was united to the historical '''Diocese of Anagni'''. The diocese is a [[suffragan]] of the [[Diocese of Rome]].<ref name=CathHierAnagniAlatri>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/danag.html \"Diocese of Anagni-Alatri\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 23, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathAnagniAlatri>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/anag0.htm \"Diocese of Anagni-Alatri\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 14, 2016</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=October 2016}}\nDespite the usual claims of foundation in the apostolic age, there is no evidence of Christianity in [[Anagni]] until the 4th century, and, as a bishopric, the diocese first appears in history in the fifth century.<ref>Lanzoni, p. 166: \"L'autore di una Vita di s. Pietro (''BHL'', 6699), vescovo di Anagni (\u2020 3 agosto 1105), dice della chiesa anagnina: \u00ab fundatam primitus apostolicis fundamentis, reparatam subventione dispositionis divinae \u00bb; ma si tratta di espressioni vaghe, comuni agli scrittori del XII e XIII secolo.\"</ref> Felix, Bishop of Anagni, was present at the Lateran Synod of [[Pope Felix III]] held in 487.<ref>[[Mansi people|Mansi]]. VII, 1171.{{full citation needed|date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a later century the Bishopric of Anagni obtained some attention because its occupant received special consideration from the popes. [[Zacharias of Anagni]] was one of the legates of [[Pope Nicholas I]] at the [[Council of Constantinople (861)|Council of Constantinople]] in 861, to deal with the election of [[Photios I of Constantinople|Photius]] to the patriarchate of Constantinople. Zacharias disobeyed his instructions, however, and entered into communion with the excommunicated schismatic Photius, and was therefore excommunicated himself and deposed from his bishopric of Anagni by Pope Nicholas, in his fourth Roman synod of 863.<ref>Pope Nicholas I's actions were fully explained in his letter (''Epistle VII'') to the Emperor Michael. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_015,_LT.pdf Tomus XV] (Venice: A. Zatta 1770), p. 178-186. Ughelli I, p. 308. Cappelletti VI, p. 277.</ref>\n\n[[Stephen of Anagni]], a native of Rome and son of a Roman priest named Joannes, became Bishop of Anagni, and was consecrated by [[Pope Formosus]] (891\u2013896). On the death of Formosus, and after the fifteen-day reign of Boniface VI (April 896), Stephen became Pope. He summoned and presided over the notorious \"[[Cadaver synod]]\", which put the dead body of Pope Formosus on trial, convicted him, and ordered his body thrown into the Tiber River.<ref>{{cite book|author=Horace Kinder Mann|title=The Lives of the Popes in the Early Middle Ages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T5EOAQAAIAAJ|volume=Vol. IV, 891-999|year=1910|publisher=Kegan Paul, Trench, Tr\u00fcbner|location=London|pages=68\u201385}}</ref> Pope Stephen ruled for one year, three months, and eighteen days, and was then deposed, imprisoned, and strangled.<ref>Stephen's consecration by Formosus occurs first in the 15th century recension of the ''Liber Pontificalis''; in earlier recensions he is only called \"episcopus Campaniae\", and there is no mention of consecration. {{cite book|author=Louis Duchesne|title=Le Liber pontificalis: texte, introduction et commentaire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=alU-AAAAYAAJ|volume=Vol. II, pars 1|year=1892|publisher=E. Thorin|location=Paris|language=Latin|page=229}}</ref>\n\nFour natives of Anagni, all members of the same family, became popes: [[Pope Innocent III|Innocent III]] (1198-1216);<ref>Innocent was born Lothar dei Conti di Segni, and he had been a Canon of the cathedral of Anagni. {{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|pages=136\u2013138}}</ref> [[Pope Gregory IX|Gregory IX]] (1227\u20131241);<ref>Ugo dei Conti di Segni was a nephew of Innocent III, and was also a Canon of Anagni. {{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|pages=136\u2013138}}</ref>  [[Pope Alexander IV|Alexander IV]] (1254\u20131261);<ref>In the bull \"Ex Assumpto\" of 8 September 1257, Pope Alexander recalls the details of his upbringing in Anagni; he had been a Canon of the cathedral Chapter: Ughelli I, p. 315. {{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|page=194}}</ref> and [[Pope Boniface VIII|Boniface VIII]] (1294-1303). Numerous popes made Anagni their summer residence, or their refuge from Romans and emperors.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alessandro De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|year=1749|publisher=nella stamperia di S. Michele per Ottavio Puccinelli|location=Roma|language=Italian|pages=105\u2013110}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a local legend of Anagni, [[Thomas Becket]] in his exile from England, was received in 1169 at Anagni by the canons,<ref>The alleged visit is mentioned neither in Becket's correspondence nor in the lives written about him. De Magistris (1749), p. 107. {{cite book|author=John Morris|title=The Life and Martyrdom of Saint Thomas Becket, Archbishop of Canterbury|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eWYNAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA511|edition=second|year=1885|publisher=Burns and Oates|location=London & New York|page=511}}</ref> and a chapel, which had once been a Mithraeum, was consecrated in his honor in the crypt of the cathedral, apparently at the request of [[Henry II of England]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Herbert L. Kessler|title=Experiencing Medieval Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zB6vDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT148|year=2019|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-1-4426-0074-4|pages=148, 151, 172}}</ref>\n\nPope Boniface VIII was violently attacked at Anagni by [[Guillaume de Nogaret]], the chancellor of [[Philippe le Bel]], and [[Sciarra Colonna]]. He was so badly treated that he died two weeks later, after having fled to Rome.<ref>Julien Th\u00e9ry, \"The Pioneer of Royal Theocracy. Guillaume de Nogaret and the conflicts between Philip the Fair and the Papacy\", in: ''The Capetian Century, 1214-1314'', ed. William Chester Jordan, Jenna Rebecca Phillips (Brepols, 2017), pp. 219-259. Richard A. Newhall (1921), \"The Affair of Anagni,\" ''The Catholic Historical Review'' Vol. 7, No. 3 (October, 1921), pp. 277-295. [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/01448a.htm ''Catholic Encyclopedia'' article]. Ernest Renan (1872) \"Un mininstre du roi Philippe le Bel: Guillaume de Nogaret. Premi\u00e8re partie: L' attentat d'Anagni,\" ''Revue des Deux Mondes'', Seconde p\u00e9riode, Vol. 98, No. 2 (15 mars 1872), pp. 328-349.</ref>\n\n===Chapter===\nIn 1244, Pope Innocent IV intervened in a jurisdictional dispute between Bishop Pandulfus and the cathedral Chapter, deciding that the bishop should not have the exclusive right to name the rectors of the city churches, but that the assent of the Chapter was required for all of the bishop's nominations.<ref>{{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|page=65}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 1251, [[Pope Innocent IV]] wrote to Bishop Pandulfus about the staffing of the cathedral Chapter; he had found that there was only one priest, and no deacons or subdeacons, actually seeing to services, and he authorized the bishop and the Canons to appoint two canons and two priests who were willing to reside at the cathedral.<ref>Ughelli I, p. 314. Some of the incumbents were too old or too young to perform their duties, others were non-residential.</ref> A few years later, [[Pope Alexander IV]] (1254\u20131261) fixed the number of dignities in the Cathedral Chapter at three: the Primicerius, the Archpriest and the Vicedominus; the number of Canons was limited to twenty-four. The right to elect the Archpriest belonged to the Canons, not to the bishop.<ref>{{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|page=65}}</ref> The dignity of Provost was instituted by [[Pope Boniface VIII]] (1294\u20131303).<ref>Cappelletti VI, p. 372.</ref> In 1708, the Chapter of the cathedral of S. Maria Annunziata had one dignity, the Provost, and twenty Canons.<ref>Ughelli I, p. 306. Ritzler-Sefrin V, p. 83, note 1. The population of the city was c. 3,000 persons.</ref> The right of the Canons to elect a bishop was usurped by [[Pope John XXII]] in 1316.<ref>{{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|page=64}}</ref>\n\n===Diocesan synods===\n\nThe [[Fourth Lateran Council]] (1216) decreed that provincial synods should be held annually in each ecclesiastical province, and that each diocese should hold annual diocesan synods.<ref>Capitula, VI. ''De conciliis provincialibus'': J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_022,_LT.pdf Tomus XXII] (Venice: A. Zatta 1778), p. 991.</ref>\n\nA diocesan synod was an irregularly held, but important, meeting of the bishop of a diocese and his clergy. Its purpose was (1) to proclaim generally the various decrees already issued by the bishop; (2) to discuss and ratify measures on which the bishop chose to consult with his clergy; (3) to publish statutes and decrees of the diocesan synod, of the provincial synod, and of the Holy See.<ref name=\"XIV1842\">{{cite book|author=Benedictus XIV|title=Benedicti XIV ... De Synodo dioecesana libri tredecim|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tj0F8czA8XsC&pg=PA51|volume=Tomus primus|year=1842|publisher=Hanicq|location=Mechlin|language=Latin|pages=42\u201349|chapter=Lib. I. caput secundum. De Synodi Dioecesanae utilitate}} John Paul II, Constitutio Apostolica ''de Synodis Dioecesanis Agendis'' (March 19, 1997): [https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-89-1997-ocr.pdf ''Acta Apostolicae Sedis'' 89] (1997), pp. 706-727.</ref>\n\nA diocesan synod was held by Bishop Gaspare Viviani (1579\u20131605) on 4\u20135 March 1596.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_YlT1NSMvRBcC/mode/2up ''Constitutiones et decreta ecclesiae Anagninae. Edita, & promulgata in Synodo Dioecesana anno Domini 1596. a rev.mo D. Gaspare Viviano Vrbinati, ... episcopo'']. Roma: Typographia externarum linguarum 1597.</ref>\n\nIn 1630, Bishop Giovanni Gaspare Melis (1626\u20131642) presided over a diocesan synod, and in 1645, Bishop Sebastiano Gentile (1642\u20131646) held a diocesan synod.<ref>Both the acta of the synod of 1630 and the acta of the synod of 1645 are published in: {{cite book|author=Sebastiano Gentile|title=Constitutiones, et decreta ecclesiae Anagninae edita, & promulgata in synodo dioecesana anno Domini 1645. A reuerendissimo d. Sebastiano Gentile Fulginatensi. Eiusdem Ecclesiae Dei, & apostolicae sedis gratia episcopo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eCWoTbZI5oUC&pg=PA1|year=1645|publisher=apud Agustinum Alterium|location=Foligno|language=Latin}}</ref> Bishop Bernardino Masseri (1681\u20131695) held a diocesan synod in Anagni on 21\u201322 May 1685.\n\nBishop Giovanni Battista Bassi (1708\u20131736) presided over a diocesan synod, held in Anagni on 25\u201327 June 1713.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_v4Y7AfYUhosC/page/n9/mode/2up ''Dioecesana synodus ab illustriss. & reverendiss. D.D. Jo. Baptista Basso Anagniae episcopo, ... celebrata in ecclesia cathedrali diebus 25. 26. & 27. Junii anni 1713'']. Rome: J.M. Salvioni 1716 {{in lang|la}}.</ref> Bishop Cirillo Antonini (1778\u20131789) held a diocesan synod on 22\u201325 October 1780.<ref>''Dioecesana synodus, quam, sub faustissimis auspiciis sanctissimi in Christo patris Pii papae sexti, illustrissimus ac reverendissimus dominus d. Cyrillus Antonini, Dei et apostolicae sedis gratia episcopus Anagninus, ejusdem sanctissimi domini nostri praelatus domesticus ac pontificio solio assistens, nec non Terrae Acuti dominus, coegit, et diebus XXII, XXIII, XXIV et XXV mensis octobris anni aerae vulgaris christianae MDCCLXXX bisextilis, ecclesiae suae servandam proposuit''. Romae, MDCCLXXXI, apud Antonium Fulgoni.</ref>\n\nOn 1\u20133 September 1805, Bishop Gioacchino Tosi (1804\u20131815) presided at a diocesan synod in the Basilica Cathedral of S. Maria in Anagni.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gioacchino Tosi|title=Decreta synodi dioecesanae Anagninae habitae in Basili Cathedrali Sanctae Mariae kalendis, IV ac III non. mensis septembris anno post Christum natum MDCCV.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tpl8cTCcP8MC&pg=PA23|year=1805|publisher=typis Lazarinii typographi|location=Roma|language=Latin}}</ref>\n\n==Bishops==\n===Diocese of Anagni===\n{{expand list|date=October 2016}}\n\n====to 1200====\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n:'''...'''\n*Felix (attested 487)<ref>Bishop Felix was present at the third Roman synod of [[Pope Felix III]] on 13 March 487. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_007,_LT.pdf Tomus VII] (Florence: A. Zatta 1762), p. 1171. Lanzoni, p. 166, no. 1.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Fortunatus (attested 499, 501, 502)<ref>Lanzoni, p. 166, no. 2.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n:[Petrus (593) ''forgery'']<ref>Petrus is said to have signed a diploma in favor of S. Medard; the diploma is a forgery. There was no Petrus. Lanzoni, p. 167.</ref>\n*Pelagius (attested 595)<ref>Bishop Pelagius was present at the Roman synod of [[Pope Gregory I]] of 595. Lanzoni, p. 167, no. 3.</ref>\n:[Dominicus (595)]<ref>Ughelli I, p. 306, states that a Bishop Dominicus of Anagni was present at teh Roman synod of 595. The manuscripts state that Bishop Pelagius of Anagni was present. Bishop Dominicus was Bishop of Civitavecchia. Gams, p. 663 column 1, questions the inclusion of Dominicus. Lanzoni, p. 167, positively rejects it.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Opportunus (attested 649)<ref>Bishop Opportunus was present at the Roman synod of [[Pope Martin I]], held at the Lateran Basilica in 649. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_010,_LT.pdf Tomus X] (Florence: A. Zatta 1764), p. 867.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Mauritius (attested 680)<ref>Bishop Mauritius subscribed to the synodical letter of [[Pope Agatho]], sent to the Council of Constantinople in 680. Ughelli ''Italia sacra'' I, p. 307. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_011,_LT.pdf Tomus XI] (Florence: A. Zatta 1765), p. 310. Cappelletti, ''Le chiese d'Italia'' VI, p. 276.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Gregorius (attested 721)<ref>Bishop Gregorius attended the first Roman synod of [[Pope Gregory II]] on 5 April 721. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_012,_LT.pdf Tomus XII] (Florence: A. Zatta 1766), p. 262. Cappelletti VI, p. 276.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Cesarius (attested 743)<ref>Bishop Cesarius was present at the Roman synod of [[Pope Zacharias]] in 743 (The date of the synod is disputed; it may have been in 744). J.D. Mansi (ed.), [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_012,_LT.pdf Tomus XII], p. 384c. Cappelletti VI, p. 276.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Constantinus (attested 757, 761)<ref>Bishop Constantinus attended the Roman synod of [[Pope Paul I]] on 2 June 761. J.D. Mansi (ed.), [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_012,_LT.pdf Tomus XII], p. 384c. Cappelletti VI, p. 649. Cappelletti VI, p. 276.</ref>\n*Nigortius (attested 769)<ref>Bishop Nigortius was present at the Roman synod at the Lateran of [[Pope Stephen III]] on 12 April 769. J.D. Mansi (ed.), [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_012,_LT.pdf Tomus XII], p. 384c. Cappelletti VI, p. 276.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Romualdus (attested 826)<ref>Bishop Romualdus was present at the Roman synod of [[Pope Eugenius II]] on 15 November 826. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_014,_LT.pdf Tomus XIV] (Florence: A. Zatta 1765), p. 999. Cappelletti, ''Le chiese d'Italia'' VI, p. 277.</ref>\n*Sebastianus (before 853)<ref>Sebastianus was the immediate successor of Bishop Romualdus. He was bishop at the time of the Saracen invasions, which began in 847. Ughelli I, p. 307. Cappelletti VI, p. 277.</ref>\n*Nicholas (attested 853)<ref>Nicholas: Ughelli I, pp. 307-308. Cappelletti VI, p. 277.</ref>\n*Zacharias (attested 860\u2013863)<ref>Zacharias was sent by [[Pope Nicholas I]] as his representative to Constantinople, but he failed to do the business for which he had been sent, and engaged in activities for which he had no warrant. He was deposed and excommunicated at the Roman synod of 863. He was later restored by [[Pope Adrian II]]. Cappelletti, ''Le chiese d'Italia'' VI, p. 277. Kehr II, p. 136, no. 1.</ref>\n*Alboinus (Albinus) (attested 863\u2013869)<ref>Alboinus: Ughelli I, p. 308. Cappelletti, p. 277. Gams, p. 663, column 1.</ref>\n*Zacharias (c. 872 \u2013 after 887) (second term)<ref>The deposed Zacharias was restored by Pope Adrian II (867\u2013872). Kehr II, p. 136, no. 1, note.</ref>\n*Stephanus (c. 891\u2013896)\n:'''...'''\n*Joannes (attested 963\u2013967)<ref>Bishop Joannes was present at the Roman synod of [[Pope Leo VIII]] of 26 February 964, and at the Roman synod of [[Pope John XIII]] of 26 May 969. Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Joannes (attested 993\u2013997)<ref>Joannes (II) was present at the Lateran synod of [[Pope John XV]] on 3 February 993. Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n:[Luitardus]<ref>Ughelli I, p. 308, places Luitardus after Bishop Joannes, but offers no evidence. De Magistris, p. 126, places him in the time of [[Pope Silvester II]], but offers no evidence. Schwartz, p. 268, notes the entry of Ughelli, but doubts his episcopacy. {{cite book|author=Alessandro De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica Cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6RNLAAAAcAAJ|year=1749|publisher=Ottavio Puccinelli|location=Roma|language=italian|page=126}}</ref>\n*Trasmundus (attested 1008)<ref>Trasmundus: Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Rumaldus (11th cent.)<ref>Rumaldus (Grimaldus): Schwartz, pp. 268-269.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Benedictus (attested 1026\u20131027)<ref>Benedictus: Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Petrus (1062\u20131105)<ref>Petrus reigned for 43 years, and died on 3 August 1105. On 4 June 1109, [[Pope Paschal II]] ordered the bishops of Campania to insert into their calendars the observance of the death of Saint Peter, Bishop of Anagni, on 3 August. Kehr, pp. 137-138, no. 8. Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n*Oddo (attested 1111)<ref>Bishop Oddo (Ogdonus) attended the synod of Veroli in 1111. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_021,_LT.pdf Tomus XXI] (Venice: A. Zatta 1776), p. 49. Ughelli I, p. 309. Cappelletti VI, p. 330. Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n*Petrus<ref>Petrus had been Archpriest of the cathedral of Anagni. He was the immediate successor of Bishop Petrus. Ughelli I, p. 309. Cappelletti VI, p. 330. Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n*Ojolinus<ref>Ojolinus had been Vicedominus of the cathedral of Anagni. He was the successor of Bishop Petrus. Ughelli I, p. 309. Cappelletti VI, p. 330-331. Schwartz, p. 268.</ref>\n*Raone (attested 1133)<ref>Bishop Raone assisted [[Antipope Anacletus II|Anacletus II]] at the transfer of the remains and the consecration of the altar of S. Oliva in the cathedral of Anagni on 12 September 1133. Cappelletti VI, p. 331.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Lotarius (attested 1155)<ref>It is said that Lotarius is the same person as Eleutherius, found in a letter of [[Pope Anastasius IV]] to the Abbot of Montecassino. However Pope Anastasius addresses him as Lotarius in a letter of 30 September 1155. Cappelletti VI, p. 331. Kehr II, p. 138, no. 12.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Nuclerius (attested 1161)<ref>Nuclerius: Kehr II, pp. 138-139, nos. 14-15.</ref>\n*Asahel (attested 1179)<ref>Asahel attended the Second Lateran Council, held by [[Pope Alexander III]] in March 1179. J.D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima editio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_022,_LT.pdf Tomus XXII] (Venice: A. Zatta 1778), p. 213.</ref>\n*Joannes (attested 1180\u20131185)<ref>Joannes: Cappelletti VI, p. 334.</ref>\n*Joannes (1196\u20131220)\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n====1200 to 1700====\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Joannes (1196\u20131220)<ref>Ughelli I, pp. 309-310.</ref>\n*Joannes (1221\u2013 ? )<ref>Joannes was consecrated a bishop by [[Pope Honorius III]] personally. Ughelli I, p. 310. Eubel, ''Hierarchia catholica'' I, p. 86 with note 1.</ref>\n*Albertus (1224\u20131237)<ref>Albertus: Cappelletti VI, pp. 337-341.</ref>\n*Pandulfus (attested 1237\u20131255)<ref>Pandulfus: Cappelletti VI, pp. 341-345.</ref>\n:[Nicolaus]<ref>Ughelli I, p. 315 and 317, reports two Nicholases, one in 1257 and one in 1274, but without any documentation in either case. Cappelletti, p. 347, accepts the first Nicholas, and places him in 1257, but is vague as to the rationale. Gams, p. 663, lists the name Nicholas in 1257, but with a question mark. Eubel, p. 86, copies Gams' information. Both Gams and Eubel omit any reference to the second Nicholas, allegedly of 1274.</ref>\n*Joannes Compatre (attested 1257)<ref>Bishop Joannes was already in office on 22 April 1257. Ughelli I, pp. 315-317. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 129. Eubel I, p. 86.</ref>\n*Landulfus<ref>Lando (or Landulfus) had been a Canon of the cathedral Chapter of Anagni. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 129.</ref>\n*Petrus Gaetani (1276\u20131278)<ref>Petrus, the son of Matteo Caetani, was the uncle of Benedetto Caetani (Pope Boniface VIII). He was a Canon of the cathedral of Anagni. He was named Bishop of Sora, and in 1252 was transferred to Todi, and then to Anagni. He died in 1278. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 129. Eubel I, p. 86.</ref>\n*Petrus \n*Gerardus Pigoletti (1289\u20131290)<ref>Gerardus was elected Bishop of Anagni before 3 May 1289. Bishop Gerardus was transferred to the diocese of Spoleto by [[Pope Nicholas IV]] on 4 March 1290. He was transferred to the diocese of Arras (France) by [[Pope Boniface VIII]] on 28 March 1295. He died in 1316. Eubel I, pp. 86, 115, 461.</ref>\n*Petrus, O.Cist. (1290\u20131295)<ref>Bishop Petrus, O.P., a Spaniard, was transferred to Anagni from the diocese of Segni by [[Pope Nicholas IV]], at the request of the Chapter of Anagni. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130. Eubel I, p. 87.</ref>\n*Petrus Torrita (1295\u20131299)<ref>Petrus had been a Canon of Padua and chaplain of [[Pope Boniface VIII. He was consecrated on 20 September 1295. Bishop Petrus was transferred to the diocese of Aversa by [[Pope Boniface VIII]] on 3 August 1299. He died in 1309. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130. Eubel I, pp. 87, 123.</ref>\n*Leonardus (1299\u20131320)<ref>Leonardo of Anticoli (diocese of Anagni) had been a Canon of Anagni, then Vicedominus, Primicerius, and Archpriest. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130.</ref>\n*[[Petrus Ferri (bishop|Petrus Ferri]] (1320\u20131327)<ref>The Chapter of Anagni had elected Lando Catennacio Ferri, a fellow Canon, but he was rejected by [[Pope John XXII]]. Ferri was appointed on 7 April 1320, and consecrated by the pope personally. On 20 Mar 1327 Bishop Petrus was transferred by John XXII to the diocese of [[Bishop of Marsi|Marsi]]. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130. Eubel I, pp. 87, 327.</ref>\n*Alamannus de Galgano (1327\u20131330)<ref>De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130.</ref>\n*[[Giovanni Pagnotta]], O.S.A. (5 Nov 1330 \u2013 Mar 1341 Died)<ref>Pagnotta had been Vicar General of [[Pope Benedict XII]], and had a part in the foundation of the hospital for incurables in Rome. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130.</ref>\n*Joannes de Scrofanis (1342\u20131348)<ref>Giovanni had been a Canon of the cathedral of Rieti. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130.</ref>\n*Petrus de Grassinis (1348\u20131363)<ref>Grassini had been Bishop of Sorrento. He was transferred to Anagni on 5 November 1348 by [[Pope Clement VI]]. De Magistris, ''Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale'', p. 130.</ref>\n*Joannes Jacobi Modeli (1363\u20131382) ''Avignon Obedience''\n*Thomas Morganti, O.Cist. (1382\u20131398) ''Roman Obedience''\n*Jacobus de Trebis, O.E.S.A. (1399\u20131401)<ref>Jacobus was named Bishop of Anagni on 8 July 1399, by [[Pope Boniface IX]]. On 14 December 1401, Jacobus (Giacomo di Trevi) was named titular Bishop of Chalcedon (Turkey) by Pope Boniface, but he refused the appointment. Eubel I, pp. 87, and p. 183 note 4.</ref>\n*Angelo Afflitti (1401\u20131418)<ref>Afflitti: Eubel I, p. 87.</ref>\n*Angelotto Fosco (1418\u20131426)<ref>Fosco had been a chamberlain of [[Pope Martin V]], who named him Abbot commendatory of the monastery of S. Maria de Gloria on 14 February 1418, and consecrated him a bishop at Mantua on 20 November 1418. Fosco was transferred to the diocese of Cava on 22 May 1426. Eubel I, p. 87 with note 9; 179.</ref>\n:''Sede vacante'' (1426\u20131429)\n::Oddo Potii de Variis (1426\u20131429) ''Apostolic Administrator''<ref>Oddo was a native of Gennazzano (diocese of Palestrina), and was a subdeacon and, from 26 August 1426, the pope's treasurer. Eubel I, p. 87, note 10.</ref>\n*Francesco da Genazzano (1429\u20131451)<ref>Francesco had been a Canon of the Basilica of S. Maria Maggiore in Rome, and was a personal friend of [[Pope Martin V]]. He was appointed Bishop of Anagni on 28 January 1429. He resigned in 1451. Eubel I, p. 87 with note 11.</ref>\n*Salvatore da Genazzano (1451\u2013 ? )<ref>Salvatore had been a Canon of the cathedral Chapter of Anagni, and held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]''. Eubel II, p. 87.</ref>\n*Giovanni da Cremona (1478)<ref>Giovanni: 14 August 1478\u2013September 1478?). Eubel II, p. 87.</ref>\n*Francesco Muscambruni (1484\u20131502?)<ref>Francesco was of a family of Todi, but was born in Benevento. He was a Canon of the Lateran Basilica in Rome. He was appointed Bishop of Anagni by [[Pope Innocent VIII]] on 13 October 1484. His successor was appointed in May 1502. Cappelletti VI, p. 361. Eubel II, p. 87 with note 2.</ref>\n*Ferdinando di Lanciano (1502\u20131515)<ref>Ferdinando was a native of Gaziano. Cappelletti VI, p. 361. Eubel II, p. 87.</ref>\n*[[Giacomo Bongalli]] (1515\u20131516)<ref>Bongalli was appointed Bishop of Anagni on 16 December 1515. On 5 November 1516, Bongalli was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Nepi e Sutri|Nepi e Sutri]] by [[Pope Leo X]]. Eubel III, p. 107 with notes 3 and 4.</ref> \n*Cardinal [[Francesco Soderini]] (1517\u20131523 Resigned) ''Administrator''<ref>Soderini resigned on 4 March 1523, in favor of his physician. Eubel III, p. 107.</ref>\n*[[Corrado Cerbaria]] (7 Jun 1525 \u2013 1534 Died) \n*Cardinal [[Gianvincenzo Carafa]] (1534\u20131541 Resigned) ''Administrator''<ref>Cardinal Carafa was already Archbishop of Naples. He was appointed Administrator of the diocese of Anagni on 16 December 1534 by [[Pope Paul III]]. He resigned the administratorship on 26 January 1541. Cappelletti, p. 362. Eubel III, p. 107.</ref> \n*Cardinal [[Pedro Sarmiento]] (1541 Resigned) ''Administrator''<ref>Sarmiento was appointed administrator of the diocese of Anagni by [[Pope Paul III]] on 28 January 1541. He resigned the administratorship nine weeks later, on 6 April 1541. Cappelletti, p. 362. Eubel III, p. 107.</ref> \n*[[Miguel Torcella]] (6 Apr 1541 \u2013 1572 Died)<ref>Torcella: Cappelletti, p. 362.</ref>\n*[[Benedetto Lomellini]] (17 Mar 1572 \u2013 24 Jul 1579 Died)<ref>{{cite book|author=De Magistris|title=Istoria della citt\u00e0 e S. Basilica cattedrale d'Anagni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJEtv63HePkC|pages=132\u2013133}}</ref> \n*[[Gaspare Viviani]] (3 Aug 1579 \u2013 25 Jan 1605 Died)<ref name=CathHierGaspViviani>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bvivianig.html \"Bishop Gaspare Viviani\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016.{{Self-published source|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Vittorio Guarini]] (1605\u20131607)<ref>Guarini was born in Piperno (diocese of Terracina). He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]''. He was appointed Bishop of Anagni by [[Pope Paul V]] on 4 July 1605. He died before 25 June 1607, the date of the appointment of his successor. Cappelletti VI, pp. 363-364. Gauchat, ''Hierarchia catholica'' IV, p. 82 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Antonio Seneca]] (1607\u20131626)<ref>Seneca was a native of Norcia. He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'', and was a protonotary apostolic. He was a familiar of Archbishop [[Carlo Borromeo]] of Milan, and was Dean in the cathedral Chapter of Milan, as well as Borromeo's Vicar General. On 25 June 1607, he was appointed Bishop of Anagni by Pope Paul V. He held a diocesan synod  He died in Rome on 11 (or 29) August 1626. Cappelletti VI, p. 364. Gauchat, p. 82 with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Gian Gaspare Melis]] (16 Sep 1626 \u2013 Jan 1642 Died)\n*[[Sebastiano Gentili]] (24 Mar 1642 \u2013 3 Dec 1646 Resigned)<ref name=CathHierSebGent>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bgentis.html \"Bishop Sebastiano Gentili\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved January 20, 2017.{{Self-published source|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Pier Francesco Filonardi]] (3 Dec 1646 \u2013 1662 Died) \n*[[Gian Lorenzo Castiglioni]] (13 Mar 1662 \u20131680)<ref>On 9 December 1680, Castiglioni was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Acquapendente|Acquapendente]] by [[Pope Innocent XI]]. Gauchat, p. 82.</ref>\n*[[Bernardino Masseri]] (23 Jun 1681 \u2013 Aug 1695 Died)<ref name=HierarchiaV>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi|volume=Vol. V|page=83|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|language=Latin}}</ref>\n{{Div col end}}\n\n====from 1700 to 1987====\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Pietro Paolo Gerardi]] (21 May 1696 \u2013 31 May 1708 Died)<ref>Gerardi: Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 83 with note 3.</ref>\n*Giovanni Battista Bassi (3 Oct 1708 \u2013 19 Dec 1736 Died)<ref>Bassi: Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 83 with note 4.</ref>\n::Bartolomeo de Vulsinio, O.F.M.Observ. (1729\u20131736)<ref>Bartolomeo de Vulsino was appointed Coadjutor-bishop of Anagni and titular Bishop of Pompeiopolis on 23 March 1729 by [[Pope Benedict XIII]]. Vulsinio died before 5 December 1736. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' V, p. 83 with note 3.</ref>\n*Giovanni Antonio Bacchetoni (1737\u20131749)<ref>Bacchetoni was born at Preci (diocese of Spoleto) in 1689. He held the degree of ''[[Doctor of both laws|Doctor in utroque iure]]'' from the University of Macerata (1719). He was a Canon of the cathedral Chapter of Spoleto. He held the post of Vicar General of the diocese of Spoleto, then of Fano, then of Todi, then of Rimini. He was appointed Vicar Apostolic of Anagni on 5 December 1736, due to the decrepit condition of Bishop Bassi. He was named Bishop of Anagni on 11 February 1737. On 1 December 1749 Bishop Bacchetoni was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Recanati e Loreto|Recanati e Loreto]] by [[Pope Benedict XIV]]. He died on 30 August 1767. Cappelletti VI, pp. 365-366. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VI, p. 81 with note 2; 354 with note 3.</ref>  \n*Domenico Monti (19 Jan 1750 \u20131766<ref>)On 14 April 1766, Monti was transferred to the archdiocese of [[Archbishop of Urbino|Urbino]]. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 81 with note 3.</ref> \n*Giovanni Battista Filipponi Tenderini (14 Apr 1766 \u2013 11 Sep 1778 Resigned)<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 81 with note 4.</ref>  \n*Cirillo Antonini (28 Sep 1778 \u2013 20 Jan 1789 Died)<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 81 with note 5.</ref>  \n*Giovanni Devoti (30 Mar 1789 \u2013 26 Mar 1804 Resigned)<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 81 with note 6.</ref>  \n*[[Gioacchino Tosi]] (26 Mar 1804 \u2013 21 Mar 1815 Resigned)<ref>Tosi had been Secretary of State for Latin Letters of [[Pope Pius VI]]. He pronounced the Pope's funeral oration in the Vatican Basilica in 1802, on the return of the papal remains from France. He was named Bishop of Anagni by Pius VII on 16 March 1804, and, on 3 April 1804, he was consecrated a bishop by Pope Pius. In February 1810, he was asked by Count Luigi Pecci of Carpineto to officiate at the baptism on his son, Gioacchino, but he had to decline. He was suspended from his episcopal functions by Pius VII on his return from captivity in France, on suspicion of his having become a Mason, and for having cooperated with the French occupation by taking oaths of loyalty and obedience; he was compelled to resign the diocese on 21 March 1815. He died in November 1837. {{cite book|title=Il divin salvatore periodico settimanale romano|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y10Q1A3RvIUC&pg=PA709|volume=Vol. 17|year=1881|publisher=Tip. Salviucci|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=709}} Ludwig von Pastor, ''The History of the Popes, from the Close of the Middle Ages'', Volume 40, p. 393. Cappelletti, p. 366. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VII, p. 72. Gioacchino Giammaria, \"La cospirazione patriottica nella Delegazione apostolica di Frosinone,\" {{cite book|author=AA. VV.|title=Risorgimento e territori. Contributi al processo unitario dall'area laziale: ivista Storica del Lazio. Numero monografico|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-Q81zE736HQC&pg=PA168|series=Rivista storica del Lazio XV-XVI|year=2013|publisher=Gangemi Editore spa|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-492-7541-4|page=168}}</ref> \n:''Sede vacante'' (1815\u20131838)<ref>Cappelletti VI, pp. 366-367.</ref>\n::Luca Amici, Bishop of Ferentino (1815) ''Administrator''\n::Francesco Maria Biordi, titular Bishop of Dulma (1816) ''Administrator''<ref>Biordi died on 7 October 1817.</ref>\n::Giuseppe Maria Lais, titular Bishop of Hippo (1817-1834) ''Administrator''\n::Pier Francesco Muccioli, O.F.M.Conv., titular Bishop of Messene (1834\u20131838) ''Administrator'' \n*Vincenzo Annovazzi (15 Feb 1838 \u2013 12 Sep 1846 Resigned)<ref>Annovazzi was born in Civitavecchia in 1779. He was named titular Bishop of Leros (Aegean) and Auxiliary Bishop of Civitavecchia on 3 July 1826 by [[Pope Leo XII]]. On 15 February 1838, he was transferred to the diocese of Anagni by [[Pope Gregory XVI]]. He resigned on 12 February 1846, for reasons of health, and was appointed titular Bishop of Iconium (Turkey). He died on 4 August 1850. Cappelletti VI, p. 367. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VII, pp. 73, 237; VIII, p. 318.</ref> \n*Pietro Paolo Trucchi, C.M. (1846\u20131857)<ref>Trucchi was born in Tivoli in 1807. He was a priest of the Congregation of S. Vincenzo di Paoli. He was appointed Bishop of Anagni on 21 September 1846 by Pope Pius IX. On 21 December 1857, Trucchi was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Forli|Forl\u00ec]] by [[Pope Pius IX]]. He died on 21 January 1887. Ritzler-Sefrin, ''Hierarchia catholica'' VIII, pp. 98, 275.</ref> \n*Clemente Pagliaro (21 Dec 1857 \u2013 9 Mar 1875) \n*Domenico Pietromarchi (31 Mar 1875 \u2013 7 Feb 1894) \n*Antonino Sardi (18 May 1894 \u2013 8 Jul 1912 Resigned) \n*Silvio Gasperini (2 Dec 1912 \u2013 24 Oct 1923) \n*Luigi Mazzini (9 Nov 1923 \u2013 24 Jun 1926 Resigned) \n*Gaudenzio Manuelli (8 Jul 1927 \u20131931)<ref>On 18 February 1931, Manuelli was transferred to the diocese of [[Archbishop of L'Aquila|L'Aquila]] by [[Pope Pius XI]].</ref> \n*Attilio Adinolfi (5 May 1931 \u2013 1 Sep 1945) \n*Giovanni Battista Piasentini, C.S.Ch. (18 Feb 1946 \u20131952)<ref>On 31 January 1952, Piasentini was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Chioggia|Chioggia]] by [[Pope Pius XII.</ref> \n*Enrico Romolo Compagnone, O.C.D. (10 Mar 1953 \u20131972)<ref>On 9 March 1972, Compagnone was transferred to the diocese of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Latina-Terracina-Sezze-Priverno|Terracina-Latina, Priverno e Sezze]] by [[Pope Paul VI]].</ref> \n*Vittorio Ottaviani (30 Nov 1972 \u20131973)<ref>On 10 November 1973, Ottaviani was transferred to the diocese of [[Bishop of Marsi|Marsi]] by [[Pope Paul VI.</ref> \n*Umberto Florenzani (21 Dec 1973 \u2013 23 Feb 1987 Died)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Diocese of Anagni-Alatri===\n[[Image:San Paolo Alatri 3.jpg|thumb|right|235px|Co-cathedral in [[Alatri]]]]\n''30 September 1986 United with the [[Diocese of Alatri]]''\n\n*Luigi Belloli (7 Dec 1987 \u2013 6 Mar 1999 Retired) \n*Francesco Lambiasi (6 Mar 1999 \u2013 28 Jun 2002 Resigned) \n*Lorenzo Loppa (28 Jun 2002 \u2013 )<ref>Loppa was born in Segni in 1947. He became a priest in 1971, and was named Bishop of Anagni on 28 June 2002. He was consecrated a bishop on 22 September 2002. Diocesi di Anagni-Alatri, [http://www.diocesianagnialatri.it/vescovo.html \"Vescovo\"]; retrieved: 13 April 2020.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n===Sources for lists of bishops===\n\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon|pages=663\u2013664|language=Latin}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica|volume=Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|