f the Blessed Virgin Mary, Johnstown\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Schools==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Preschools===\n* All Saints Catholic School, Cresson\n* Divine Mercy Catholic Academy, Johnstown\n* Holy Name School, Ebensburg\n* Holy Trinity Catholic School, Altoona, Hollidaysburg\n* Lock Haven Catholic School, Lock Haven\n* Northern Cambria Catholic School, Nicktown\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart School, Portage (also offers Kindergarten)\n* Our Lady of Victory Preschool, State College\n* Saint Benedict School, Carrolltown\n* Saint Matthew School, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael School, Loretto\n* Saint Patrick School, Newry\n* Saint Peter School, Somerset\n* Saint Thomas School, Bedford\n\n===Elementary schools===\n* All Saints Catholic School, Cresson\n* Divine Mercy Catholic Academy, Johnstown\n* Holy Name School, Ebensburg\n* Holy Trinity Catholic School, Altoona, Hollidaysburg\n* Lock Haven Catholic School, Lock Haven\n* Northern Cambria Catholic School, Nicktown\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart School, Portage (also offers Kindergarten)\n* Our Lady of Victory Preschool, State College\n* Saint Benedict School, Carrolltown\n* Saint Matthew School, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael School, Loretto\n* Saint Patrick School, Newry\n* Saint Peter School, Somerset\n* Saint Thomas School, Bedford\n\n===Middle schools===\n* All Saints Catholic School, Cresson\n* Divine Mercy Catholic Academy, Johnstown\n* Holy Name School, Ebensburg\n* Holy Trinity Catholic School, Altoona, Hollidaysburg\n* Lock Haven Catholic School, Lock Haven\n* Northern Cambria Catholic School, Nicktown\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart School, Portage (also offers Kindergarten)\n* Our Lady of Victory Preschool, State College\n* Saint Benedict School, Carrolltown\n* Saint Matthew School, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael School, Loretto\n* Saint Patrick School, Newry\n* Saint Peter School, Somerset\n* Saint Thomas School, Bedford\n\n===High schools===\n* [[Bishop Carroll High School (Ebensburg, Pennsylvania)|Bishop Carroll High School]], Ebensburg\n* [[Bishop Guilfoyle High School]], Altoona\n* [[Bishop McCort High School]], Johnstown\n* [[Saint Joseph's Catholic Academy (Boalsburg, Pennsylvania)|Saint Joseph's Catholic Academy]], Boalsburg\n\n===Colleges and universities===\n* [[Mount Aloysius College]], Cresson\n* [[Saint Francis University]], Loretto\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Sexual abuse controversy==\nIn December 2004, Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown priest Rev. Elwood F. Figurelle pled guilty to possession of child pornography and received a 15-21 month prison sentence.<ref name=anotherpriest>http://www.bishop-accountability.org/news3/2004_12_22_AP_ElwoodFigurelle_ElwoodFigurelle_1.htmp</ref> He was also ordered to pay a $20,000 fine, participate in counseling and undergo three years of supervised release.<ref name=anotherpriest /> In September 2014, another Diocese, Joseph D. Maurizo Jr. was arrested and charged with possession of child pornography and molesting boys at an orphanage in Honduras.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/27/us/priest-in-sexual-abuse-case-was-reported-to-diocese-5-years-ago-records-show.html</ref> On September 22, 2015, Maurizo was convicted on three counts of sex abuse, one count of possession of child pornography, and one count of illegally transferring money to pay the boys he sexually abused in Honduras.<ref>https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2015/09/22/suspended-priest-convicted-of-charges-in-sex-tourism-case/</ref><ref name=sentenceupheld>https://www.tribdem.com/news/court-upholds-priest-s-sex-abuse-conviction-involving-orphans-in/article_c11bb4f6-7177-11e7-9621-cb7eb86c0342.html</ref> In March 2016, Maurizo received a 17-year prison sentence, which he will serve in Pennsylvania.<ref>https://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/03/altoona-johnstown_priest_sente.html</ref> His sentence was upheld in 2017 after he was denied an appeal to overturn the convictions.<ref>https://www.pennlive.com/news/2017/07/disgraced_catholic_priest_lose.html</ref><ref name=sentenceupheld />\n\nOn March 1, 2016, a Pennsylvania grand jury investigating the Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona\u2013Johnstown [https://www.attorneygeneral.gov/uploadedFiles/MainSite/Content/Related_Content/PressReleases/GJ%20Diocese%20Report.pdf reported] that at least 50 priests and others associated with the church had abused hundreds of children across nearly half a century, and that diocesan leadership actively concealed the abuse.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/state/2016/03/01/Staggering-abuse-cover-up-in-Altoona-Johnstown-diocese-grand-jury-says/stories/201603010091|title=Grand jury: Altoona diocese concealed sex abuse of hundreds of children by priests|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2016-03-02}}</ref> Much of the abuse happened [http://www.post-gazette.com/news/state/2016/03/01/Staggering-abuse-cover-up-in-Altoona-Johnstown-diocese-grand-jury-says/stories/201603010091 between the 1940s and 1980s], but many of the victims came forward in more recent decades to report the priest to the diocese. While the report<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.attorneygeneral.gov/uploadedFiles/MainSite/Content/Related_Content/PressReleases/GJ%20Diocese%20Report.pdf|title=A Report of the Thirty-Seventh Statewide Investigating Grand Jury|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=March 2, 2016|via=}}</ref> suggested that local law enforcement and prosecutors should have been more aggressive in pursuing victims' stories, it says two former bishops were primarily to blame for the decades of concealment: James Hogan, who served from 1966 to 1986 and died in 2005, and Joseph Adamec, who served from 1987 to 2011 and is now retired. Those bishops \"took actions that further endangered children as they placed their desire to avoid public scandal over the well-being of innocent children ... Priests were returned to ministry with full knowledge they were child predators.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> Monsignor Michael Servinsky, who served under Hogan, Adamec and the current Bishop, Mark Bartchak, were called to testify before a grand jury.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/accountability/grand-jury-report-reveals-decades-clergy-sex-abuse-altoona-johnstown-diocese|title=Grand jury report reveals decades of clergy sex abuse in Altoona-Johnstown diocese|date=2 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> In his testimony, Bartchak acknowledged that dozens of Catholic figures who were stationed in the Diocese's small town communities abused children between the 1950s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/mar/08/catholic-priest-child-sex-abuse-ebensburg-pennsylvania|title='He was a monster': how priest child abuse tore apart Pennsylvania towns|first=Joanna|last=Walters|date=8 March 2016|website=the Guardian|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> Though it was also acknowledged that Adamec had created a system to ensure that hush money would be supplied to the victims of sex abuse in the Diocese,<ref name=\":0\" /> Pennsylvania Attorney General [[Kathleen Kane]], herself a Catholic,<ref name=\":0\" /> refused to file any criminal charges by the time the testimony was made public in March 2016.<ref name=\":0\" />  Servinsky had also been executive to Bishop Hogan's estate, and, along with Adamec, was named as a co-defendant in a lawsuit which began against accused priest Charles Bodziak which started in 2016.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.tribdem.com/news/blair-county-attorney-announces-new-civil-lawsuits-against-suspended-priest/article_3418e194-37aa-11e6-a6e5-bf8a61db9ba5.html |title=Blair County attorney announces new civil lawsuits against suspended priest |last= |first= |date= |publisher= Tribune-Democrat |access-date= October 12, 2018}}</ref> The lawsuit against Bodziak was dismissed in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribdem.com/news/judge-tosses-lawsuit-against-suspended-priest/article_9ef41162-e3a9-11e7-a2a4-5780921349b5.html|title=Judge tosses lawsuit against suspended priest|first=David Hurst|last=dhurst@tribdem.com|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite identifying hundreds of cases of suspected abuse, the grand jury and the Pennsylvania Office of the Attorney General were not able to recommend criminal charges, because many of the cases were too old, and the [http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/03/altoona_diocese_catholic_clerg.html statute of limitations] for criminal prosecution had elapsed<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/03/altoona_diocese_catholic_clerg.html|title=Priests and church leaders sexually abused hundreds of children in Altoona Diocese: AG office|website=PennLive.com|access-date=2016-03-02}}</ref> [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|Bishop]] [[James John Hogan]] and Bishop [[Joseph Victor Adamec]] are noted because they covered up abuse and safeguarded the Roman Catholic Church from bad publicity rather than protecting innocent children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnhi.com/featured_stories/staggering-priest-sex-abuse-disclosed-in-pennsylvania-diocese-by-grand/article_1f102e74-dffd-11e5-81d0-2fcce7c1f10a.html|title=\u2018Staggering\u2019 priest sex abuse disclosed in Pennsylvania diocese by grand jury|first=CNHI News|last=Service|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany of those listed by the Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown are now deceased.<ref name=judgement>https://www.dioceseaj.org/list-of-priests/</ref> However, Maurizo remains incarcerated.<ref name=judgement /> Three of the accused clergy who are still alive have been laicized and two were removed from public ministry.<ref name=judgement />\n\nFormer Erie priest and current Bishop of Altoona-Johnstown [[Mark Bartchak]] was also criticized in the August 2018 grand jury investigation for his handling of 2005 investigation against former Erie priest William Presley.<ref name=aug14>{{cite web|url=http://www.starbeacon.com/news/grand-jury-report-links-altoona-johnstown-bishop-to-abuse-case/article_0add87b9-f31e-5d56-be64-f45de8b20ef9.html|title=Grand jury report links Altoona-Johnstown bishop to abuse case and cover-up in Erie|first=Dave Sutor CNHI News|last=Service|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>  Bartchak was assigned by the Vatican during this time to investigate claims against Presley, who served in the Erie Diocese between 1963 and 1986, and continuously re-interviewed a male victim who previously disclosed his alleged abuse to the diocese in 1982, 1987 and 2002.<ref name=aug14 />  On Aug. 25, 2005, Bartchak sent a secret memo to then-Erie Bishop Donald Walter Trautman.<ref name=aug14 />  Parts of the memo read \u201cI was not surprised to learn from other witnesses from the Elk County area, that there are likely to be other victims\u201d and that \"it is likely that there may be others who were also of the age for the offenses to be considered delicts, but to what end is it necessary to follow every lead?\u201d<ref name=aug14 />  Bartchak also stated in another secret memo following a meeting with Trautman on August 29, 2005 \"Bishop Trautman decided that in order to preclude further scandal, these additional witnesses should not be contacted, especially given the fact that it is not likely that they will lead to information concerning delicts involving minors under 16 years of age.\u201d<ref name=aug14 />\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1913CatholicEnc|Diocese of Altoona}}\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Philadelphia|Ecclesiastical Province of Philadelphia]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ajdiocese.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown Official Site]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Philadelphia}}\n{{Altoona, Pennsylvania}}\n{{coord|40.45369|-78.39403|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-PA|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona\u2013Johnstown| ]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1901]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century|Altoona-Johnstown]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Altoona-Johnstown]]\n[[Category:Altoona, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1901 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Altoona-Johnstown\n| latin             = Dioecesis Altunensis-Johnstoniensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament - Altoona, Pennsylvania 13.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament\n| coat              = Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona\u2013Johnstown.svg \n| coat_size         = 150px\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = {{flag|United States of America}}\n| territory         = [[Pennsylvania]] counties of [[Bedford County, Pennsylvania|Bedford]], [[Blair County, Pennsylvania|Blair]], [[Cambria County, Pennsylvania|Cambria]], [[Centre County, Pennsylvania|Centre]], [[Clinton County, Pennsylvania|Clinton]], [[Fulton County, Pennsylvania|Fulton]], [[Huntingdon County, Pennsylvania|Huntingdon]] and [[Somerset County, Pennsylvania|Somerset]]\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of Philadelphia|Philadelphia]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 6,674\n| population        = 678,000\n| population_as_of  = 2012\n| catholics         = 109,500\n| catholics_percent = 16.2\n| parishes          = 88\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = May 30, 1901 Diocese of Altoona<br>October 9, 1957 Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament (Altoona, Pennsylvania)|Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament]] (Altoona)\n| cocathedral       = [[St. John Gualbert Cathedral (Johnstown, Pennsylvania)|St. John Gualbert Cathedral]] (Johnstown)\n| patron            = Mary, Mother of the Church <ref>{{cite web|url=http://saints.sqpn.com/patrons-of-the-diocese-of-altoona-johnstown-pennsylvania/|title=patrons of the Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown, Pennsylvania|date=20 April 2009|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n| priests           = 131\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[Mark Leonard Bartchak]]<br>Bishop of Altoona-Johnstown\n| metro_archbishop  = \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.ajdiocese.org ajdiocese.org]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n[[File:St. John Gualbert Cathedral - Johnstown, Pennsylvania 03.jpg|right|260px|thumb|St. John Gualbert Cathedral in Johnstown]]\n[[File:Basilica of St. Michael the Archangel - Loretto, Pennsylvania 03.jpg|thumb|260px|Basilica of St. Michael the Archangel in Loretto]]\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona\u2013Johnstown''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Altunensis-Johnstoniensis}}) is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[diocese]] in [[Pennsylvania]]. \n\nIt was established on May 30, 1901, as the Diocese of Altoona. On October 9, 1957, the name was changed to the Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown. \n\nIt consists of [[Bedford County, Pennsylvania|Bedford]], [[Blair County, Pennsylvania|Blair]], [[Cambria County, Pennsylvania|Cambria]], [[Centre County, Pennsylvania|Centre]], [[Clinton County, Pennsylvania|Clinton]], [[Fulton County, Pennsylvania|Fulton]], [[Huntingdon County, Pennsylvania|Huntingdon]] and [[Somerset County, Pennsylvania|Somerset]] Counties. \n\nThe diocese also sponsors ''[[Proclaim!]]'', a weekly Catholic news show, and a weekly live mass from St. John Gualbert Cathedral in Johnstown.\n\nThe seat of the bishop is in the [[Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament (Altoona, Pennsylvania)|Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament]].\n\n==Bishops==\nThe bishops of the diocese and their tenures of service:\n\n===Bishops of Altoona===\n# [[Eugene A. Garvey]] (1901-1920)\n# [[John Joseph McCort]] (1920-1936)\n# [[Richard Thomas Guilfoyle]] (1936-1957)\n\n===Bishops of Altoona-Johnstown===\n# [[Howard Joseph Carroll]] (1957-1960)\n# [[Joseph Carroll McCormick]] (1960-1966), appointed [[Diocese of Scranton|Bishop of Scranton]]\n# [[James John Hogan]] (1966-1986)\n# [[Joseph Victor Adamec]] (1987-2011)\n# [[Mark Leonard Bartchak]] (2011-present)\n\n==Parishes==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* All Saints, Boswell\n* [[Basilica of St. Michael the Archangel (Loretto, Pennsylvania)|Basilica of Saint Michael the Archangel]], Loretto\n* Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament, Altoona\n* Church of the Transfiguration, Conemaugh\n* Good Shepherd, State College\n* Holy Family, Colver\n* Holy Family, Hooversville\n* Holy Name, Ebensburg\n* Holy Rosary, Altoona\n* Holy Spirit, Lock Haven\n* Immaculate Conception, Dudley\n* Immaculate Conception, New Germany\n* Most Holy Trinity, Huntingdon\n* Most Holy Trinity, South Fork\n* Our Lady of Assumption Chapel, Altoona\n* Our Lady of Fatima, Altoona\n* Our Lady of Lourdes, Altoona\n* Our Lady of Mount Carmel, Altoona\n* Our Lady of Victory, State College\n* Our Lady of the Alleghenies, Lilly\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart, Portage\n* Our Lady Queen of Angels, Central City\n* Our Mother of Sorrows, Johnstown\n* Penn State Catholic Campus Ministry, State College\n* Prince of Peace, Northern Cambria\n* Queen of Archangels, Clarence\n* Queen of Peace, Patton\n* Resurrection, Johnstown\n* Sacred Heart, Altoona\n* Saint Aloysius, Cresson\n* Saint Andrew, Johnstown\n* Saint Anne, Davidsville\n* Saint Anne, Johnstown\n* Saint Anthony of Padua, Windber\n* Saint Augustine, St. Augustine\n* Saint Bartholomew, Wilmore\n* Saint Bernard, Hastings\n* Saint Benedict, Carrolltown\n* Saint Benedict, Geistown\n* Saint Catherine of Siena, Duncansville\n* Saint Catherine of Siena, Mount Union\n* Saint Clare of Assisi, Johnstown\n* Saint Clement, Johnstown\n* Saint Demetrius, Gallitzin\n* Saint Elizabeth Ann Seton, Windber\n* Saint Francis of Assisi, Johnstown \n* Saint Francis Xavier, Cresson\n* St. Gregory, MacDonaldton\n* Saint Joan of Arc, Frugality\n* Saint John, Summerhill\n* [[Cathedral of Saint John Gualbert|Saint John Gualbert Cathedral]], Johnstown\n* Saint John the Baptist, New Baltimore\n* Saint John the Evangelist, Altoona\n* Saint John the Evangelist, Bellefonte\n* Saint John the Evangelist, Everett\n* Saint John Vianney, Mundy's Corner\n* Saint Joseph, Bellwood\n* Saint Joseph, Portage\n* Saint Joseph, Renovo\n* Saint Joseph, Williamsburg\n* Saint Kateri Tekakwitha, Penns Valley\n* Saint Mark, Altoona\n* Saint Mary (Immaculate Conception), Altoona\n* Saint Mary, Hollidaysburg\n* Saint Mary, Nanty Glo\n* Saint Mary, Pocahontas\n* Saint Mary, Shade Gap\n* Saint Mary Chapel, Snow Shoe\n* Saint Matthew, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael, Hollidaysburg\n* Saint Michael, Johnstown\n* Saint Michael, Saint Michael\n* Saint Michael, West Salisbury\n* Saint Monica, Chest Springs\n* Saint Nicholas, Nicktown\n* Saint Patrick, Johnstown\n* Saint Patrick, Newry\n* Saint Peter, Somerset\n* Saint Rose of Lima, Altoona\n* Saint Stephen, McConnellsburg\n* Saint Therese of the Child Jesus, Altoona\n* Saint Therese of the Child Jesus, Johnstown\n* Saint Thomas, Bedford\n* Saint Thomas Aquinas, Ashville\n* Saint Thomas More, Roaring Spring\n* Saints Cyril & Methodius, Windber\n* Saints Gregory & Barnabas, Johnstown\n* Saints Peter & Paul, Philipsburg\n* Saints Philip & James, Meyersdale\n* Seven Dolors of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Beans Cove\n* Visitation of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Johnstown\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Schools==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Preschools===\n* All Saints Catholic School, Cresson\n* Divine Mercy Catholic Academy, Johnstown\n* Holy Name School, Ebensburg\n* Holy Trinity Catholic School, Altoona, Hollidaysburg\n* Lock Haven Catholic School, Lock Haven\n* Northern Cambria Catholic School, Nicktown\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart School, Portage (also offers Kindergarten)\n* Our Lady of Victory Preschool, State College\n* Saint Benedict School, Carrolltown\n* Saint Matthew School, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael School, Loretto\n* Saint Patrick School, Newry\n* Saint Peter School, Somerset\n* Saint Thomas School, Bedford\n\n===Elementary schools===\n* All Saints Catholic School, Cresson\n* Divine Mercy Catholic Academy, Johnstown\n* Holy Name School, Ebensburg\n* Holy Trinity Catholic School, Altoona, Hollidaysburg\n* Lock Haven Catholic School, Lock Haven\n* Northern Cambria Catholic School, Nicktown\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart School, Portage (also offers Kindergarten)\n* Our Lady of Victory Preschool, State College\n* Saint Benedict School, Carrolltown\n* Saint Matthew School, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael School, Loretto\n* Saint Patrick School, Newry\n* Saint Peter School, Somerset\n* Saint Thomas School, Bedford\n\n===Middle schools===\n* All Saints Catholic School, Cresson\n* Divine Mercy Catholic Academy, Johnstown\n* Holy Name School, Ebensburg\n* Holy Trinity Catholic School, Altoona, Hollidaysburg\n* Lock Haven Catholic School, Lock Haven\n* Northern Cambria Catholic School, Nicktown\n* Our Lady of the Sacred Heart School, Portage (also offers Kindergarten)\n* Our Lady of Victory Preschool, State College\n* Saint Benedict School, Carrolltown\n* Saint Matthew School, Tyrone\n* Saint Michael School, Loretto\n* Saint Patrick School, Newry\n* Saint Peter School, Somerset\n* Saint Thomas School, Bedford\n\n===High schools===\n* [[Bishop Carroll High School (Ebensburg, Pennsylvania)|Bishop Carroll High School]], Ebensburg\n* [[Bishop Guilfoyle High School]], Altoona\n* [[Bishop McCort High School]], Johnstown\n* [[Saint Joseph's Catholic Academy (Boalsburg, Pennsylvania)|Saint Joseph's Catholic Academy]], Boalsburg\n\n===Colleges and universities===\n* [[Mount Aloysius College]], Cresson\n* [[Saint Francis University]], Loretto\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Sexual abuse controversy==\nIn December 2004, Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown priest Rev. Elwood F. Figurelle pled guilty to possession of child pornography and received a 15-21 month prison sentence.<ref name=anotherpriest>http://www.bishop-accountability.org/news3/2004_12_22_AP_ElwoodFigurelle_ElwoodFigurelle_1.htmp</ref> He was also ordered to pay a $20,000 fine, participate in counseling and undergo three years of supervised release.<ref name=anotherpriest /> In September 2014, another Diocese, Joseph D. Maurizo Jr. was arrested and charged with possession of child pornography and molesting boys at an orphanage in Honduras.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/27/us/priest-in-sexual-abuse-case-was-reported-to-diocese-5-years-ago-records-show.html</ref> On September 22, 2015, Maurizo was convicted on three counts of sex abuse, one count of possession of child pornography, and one count of illegally transferring money to pay the boys he sexually abused in Honduras.<ref>https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2015/09/22/suspended-priest-convicted-of-charges-in-sex-tourism-case/</ref><ref name=sentenceupheld>https://www.tribdem.com/news/court-upholds-priest-s-sex-abuse-conviction-involving-orphans-in/article_c11bb4f6-7177-11e7-9621-cb7eb86c0342.html</ref> In March 2016, Maurizo received a 17-year prison sentence, which he will serve in Pennsylvania.<ref>https://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/03/altoona-johnstown_priest_sente.html</ref> His sentence was upheld in 2017 after he was denied an appeal to overturn the convictions.<ref>https://www.pennlive.com/news/2017/07/disgraced_catholic_priest_lose.html</ref><ref name=sentenceupheld />\n\nOn March 1, 2016, a Pennsylvania grand jury investigating the Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona\u2013Johnstown [https://www.attorneygeneral.gov/uploadedFiles/MainSite/Content/Related_Content/PressReleases/GJ%20Diocese%20Report.pdf reported] that at least 50 priests and others associated with the church had abused hundreds of children across nearly half a century, and that diocesan leadership actively concealed the abuse<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/state/2016/03/01/Staggering-abuse-cover-up-in-Altoona-Johnstown-diocese-grand-jury-says/stories/201603010091|title=Grand jury: Altoona diocese concealed sex abuse of hundreds of children by priests|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|access-date=2016-03-02}}</ref>. Much of the abuse happened [http://www.post-gazette.com/news/state/2016/03/01/Staggering-abuse-cover-up-in-Altoona-Johnstown-diocese-grand-jury-says/stories/201603010091 between the 1940s and 1980s], but many of the victims came forward in more recent decades to report the priest to the diocese. While the report<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.attorneygeneral.gov/uploadedFiles/MainSite/Content/Related_Content/PressReleases/GJ%20Diocese%20Report.pdf|title=A Report of the Thirty-Seventh Statewide Investigating Grand Jury|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=March 2, 2016|via=}}</ref> suggested that local law enforcement and prosecutors should have been more aggressive in pursuing victims' stories, it says two former bishops were primarily to blame for the decades of concealment: James Hogan, who served from 1966 to 1986 and died in 2005, and Joseph Adamec, who served from 1987 to 2011 and is now retired. Those bishops \"took actions that further endangered children as they placed their desire to avoid public scandal over the well-being of innocent children ... Priests were returned to ministry with full knowledge they were child predators.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> Monsignor Michael Servinsky, who served under Hogan, Adamec and the current Bishop, Mark Bartchak, were called to testify before a grand jury.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/accountability/grand-jury-report-reveals-decades-clergy-sex-abuse-altoona-johnstown-diocese|title=Grand jury report reveals decades of clergy sex abuse in Altoona-Johnstown diocese|date=2 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> In his testimony, Bartchak acknowledged that dozens of Catholic figures who were stationed in the Diocese's small town communities abused children between the 1950s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/mar/08/catholic-priest-child-sex-abuse-ebensburg-pennsylvania|title='He was a monster': how priest child abuse tore apart Pennsylvania towns|first=Joanna|last=Walters|date=8 March 2016|website=the Guardian|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref> Though it was also acknowledged that Adamec had created a system to ensure that hush money would be supplied to the victims of sex abuse in the Diocese,<ref name=\":0\" /> Pennsylvania Attorney General [[Kathleen Kane]], herself a Catholic,<ref name=\":0\" /> refused to file any criminal charges by the time the testimony was made public in March 2016.<ref name=\":0\" />  Servinsky had also been executive to Bishop Hogan's estate, and, along with Adamec, was named as a co-defendant in a lawsuit which began against accused priest Charles Bodziak which started in 2016.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.tribdem.com/news/blair-county-attorney-announces-new-civil-lawsuits-against-suspended-priest/article_3418e194-37aa-11e6-a6e5-bf8a61db9ba5.html |title=Blair County attorney announces new civil lawsuits against suspended priest |last= |first= |date= |publisher= Tribune-Democrat |access-date= October 12, 2018}}</ref> The lawsuit against Bodziak was dismissed in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribdem.com/news/judge-tosses-lawsuit-against-suspended-priest/article_9ef41162-e3a9-11e7-a2a4-5780921349b5.html|title=Judge tosses lawsuit against suspended priest|first=David Hurst|last=dhurst@tribdem.com|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite identifying hundreds of cases of suspected abuse, the grand jury and the Pennsylvania Office of the Attorney General were not able to recommend criminal charges, because many of the cases were too old, and the [http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/03/altoona_diocese_catholic_clerg.html statute of limitations] for criminal prosecution had elapsed<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/03/altoona_diocese_catholic_clerg.html|title=Priests and church leaders sexually abused hundreds of children in Altoona Diocese: AG office|website=PennLive.com|access-date=2016-03-02}}</ref> [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|Bishop]] [[James John Hogan]] and Bishop [[Joseph Victor Adamec]] are noted because they covered up abuse and safeguarded the Roman Catholic Church from bad publicity rather than protecting innocent children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnhi.com/featured_stories/staggering-priest-sex-abuse-disclosed-in-pennsylvania-diocese-by-grand/article_1f102e74-dffd-11e5-81d0-2fcce7c1f10a.html|title=\u2018Staggering\u2019 priest sex abuse disclosed in Pennsylvania diocese by grand jury|first=CNHI News|last=Service|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany of those listed by the Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown are now deceased.<ref name=judgement>https://www.dioceseaj.org/list-of-priests/</ref> However, Maurizo remains incarcerated.<ref name=judgement /> Three of the accused clergy who are still alive have been laicized and two were removed from public ministry.<ref name=judgement />\n\nFormer Erie priest and current Bishop of Altoona-Johnstown [[Mark Bartchak]] was also criticized in the August 2018 grand jury investigation for his handling of 2005 investigation against former Erie priest William Presley.<ref name=aug14>{{cite web|url=http://www.starbeacon.com/news/grand-jury-report-links-altoona-johnstown-bishop-to-abuse-case/article_0add87b9-f31e-5d56-be64-f45de8b20ef9.html|title=Grand jury report links Altoona-Johnstown bishop to abuse case and cover-up in Erie|first=Dave Sutor CNHI News|last=Service|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>  Bartchak was assigned by the Vatican during this time to investigate claims against Presley, who served in the Erie Diocese between 1963 and 1986, and continuously re-interviewed a male victim who previously disclosed his alleged abuse to the diocese in 1982, 1987 and 2002.<ref name=aug14 />  On Aug. 25, 2005, Bartchak sent a secret memo to then-Erie Bishop Donald Walter Trautman.<ref name=aug14 />  Parts of the memo read \u201cI was not surprised to learn from other witnesses from the Elk County area, that there are likely to be other victims\u201d and that \"it is likely that there may be others who were also of the age for the offenses to be considered delicts, but to what end is it necessary to follow every lead?\u201d<ref name=aug14 />  Bartchak also stated in another secret memo following a meeting with Trautman on August 29, 2005 \"Bishop Trautman decided that in order to preclude further scandal, these additional witnesses should not be contacted, especially given the fact that it is not likely that they will lead to information concerning delicts involving minors under 16 years of age.\u201d<ref name=aug14 />\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1913CatholicEnc|Diocese of Altoona}}\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Philadelphia|Ecclesiastical Province of Philadelphia]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ajdiocese.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown Official Site]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Philadelphia}}\n{{Altoona, Pennsylvania}}\n{{coord|40.45369|-78.39403|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-PA|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona-Johnstown}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Altoona\u2013Johnstown| ]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1901]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century|Altoona-Johnstown]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Altoona-Johnstown]]\n[[Category:Altoona, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1901 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Altoona%E2%80%93Johnstown"}
